ategory:Conflicts in 1825]]\n[[Category:Denmark\u2013Spain military relations]]\n[[Category:Denmark\u2013United States military relations]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1825]]\n[[Category:Naval battles involving Denmark]]\n[[Category:Naval battles involving pirates]]\n[[Category:Naval battles involving Spain]]\n[[Category:Piracy in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Spain\u2013United States military relations]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:1820s in the Danish colonial empire]]\n", "name_user": "Snagemit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Infobox changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capture_of_the_sloop_Anne"}
{"title_page": "Like It Is (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 song by Kygo, Zara Larsson and Tyga}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Like It Is\n| type       = single\n| cover      = Kygo - Like It Is.png\n| alt        =\n| artist     = [[Kygo]], [[Zara Larsson]] and [[Tyga]]\n| album      = Golden Hour\n| released   = {{start date|2020|03|27|df=y}}\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =\n| genre      = [[Tropical house]]<ref name=\"DA Review\"/>\n| length     = 3:03\n| label      = [[Sony Music]]\n| writer   =\n* [[Kygo|Kyrre G\u00f8rvell-Dahll]]\n* [[Zara Larsson]]\n* [[Tyga|Michael Stevenson]]\n* [[Dua Lipa]]\n* [[Ritual (electronic band)|Gerard O'Connell]]\n* [[Nick Hodgson]]\n* Patrick Martin\n| producer   =\n* Kygo\n* Petey Martin\n| chronology = [[Kygo]]\n| prev_title = [[Forever Yours (Tribute)]]\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| next_title = [[I'll Wait (Kygo and Sasha Sloan song)|I'll Wait]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Zara Larsson]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Invisible\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| title      = Like It Is\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Tyga]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Contact\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| title      = Like It Is\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}{{External music video|{{YouTube|TOamHghGCfg|\"Like It Is\"}}\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Like It Is'''\" is a song by Norwegian DJ [[Kygo]], Swedish singer [[Zara Larsson]] and American rapper [[Tyga]]. It was released through [[Sony Music]] on 27 March 2020 as the lead single from Kygo's upcoming third studio album ''Golden Hour''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7908458/kygo-announces-new-single-like-it-is-featuring-zara-larsson-tyga|title=Kygo Announces New Single \"Like It Is\" Featuring Zara Larsson & Tyga|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|last=Wass|first=Mike|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nKygo announced on social media on 24 March 2020 that his third studio album was finished, and that the lead single would be out on Friday of that week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/9341792/kygo-announces-golden-hour-single-new-album|title=Kygo Is Back! The Producer Announces New Album Title & A Single Coming This Week|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Bain|first=Katie|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> Kygo also talked about spending time at home due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and \"staying positive in these tough times\"; ''[[Dancing Astronaut]]'' felt that Kygo's announcement came at a time when those in self-quarantine are \"hoping to bring some light during these dark quarantine days\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/kygo-announces-his-third-album-is-complete-first-single-to-be-released-this-friday/|title=Kygo announces his third album is complete\u2014first single to be released this Friday|website=Dancing Astronaut|last=Stack|first=Chris|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nFarrell Sweeney of ''[[Dancing Astronaut]]'' wrote that the song features \"enamoring vocals by Larsson, immediately pulling the listener into the catchy commercial fabric\" of the song. Sweeney also felt that Tyga's rap verse after the first drop was \"surprising\" and gave the song an \"unexpected twist\".<ref name=\"DA Review\">{{cite web|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/kygo-taps-zara-larsson-and-tyga-for-first-single-from-forthcoming-album/|title=Kygo taps Zara Larsson and Tyga for first single from forthcoming album|website=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|last=Sweeney|first=Farrell|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe video was released on 27 March 2020, and features Larsson and Tyga in an apartment building. It was called an \"artistic and colorful visual accompaniment\" by Sweeney.<ref name=\"DA Review\"/>\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|37|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|4|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=24 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|2|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=24 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|46|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=13&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 13, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 39\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Estonia ([[Eesti Tipp-40]])<ref name=\"estonianchart\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekspress.delfi.ee/areen/eesti-tipp-40-muusikas-dua-lipa-keeras-the-weekndil-kaela-kahekorra?id=89479383|title=EESTI TIPP-40 MUUSIKAS: Dua Lipa keeras The Weekndil kaela kahekorra|language=Estonian|last=Nestor|first=Siim|website=[[Eesti Ekspress]]|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 33\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|20|artist=Kygo,Zara Larsson,Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref name=\"frenchchart\">{{cite web|url=https://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 14, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 167\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|41|songid=1973243|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=3 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarysingle|17|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarystream|28|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland4|25|date=20200417|rowheader=true|accessdate=18 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Lithuania ([[AGATA (organization)|AGATA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.agata.lt/lt/naujienos/savaites-klausomiausi-2020w14/|title=2020 14-os savait\u0117s klausomiausi (TOP 100)|publisher=[[AGATA (organization)|AGATA]]|language=Lithuanian|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 34\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|56|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand Hot Singles ([[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4841|title=NZ Hot Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Norway ([[VG-lista]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vglista.no/topplister/topp-20-single-2020-14/|title=VG-lista \u2013 Topp 20 Single uke 14, 2020|publisher=[[VG-lista]]|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 3\n|-\n{{single chart|Portugal|140|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|23|date=20200403|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Slovakdigital|48|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Sweden ([[Sverigetopplistan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/41?dspy=2020&dspp=14|title=Veckolista Singlar, vecka 14|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 4\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|9|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=5 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|49|date=20200403|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardbubbling100|13|artist=Kygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboarddanceelectronic|5|artist=Kygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kygo}}\n{{Zara Larsson}}\n{{Tyga}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Kygo songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kygo]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Dua Lipa]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Zara Larsson]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tyga]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Nick Hodgson]]\n[[Category:Tyga songs]]\n[[Category:Zara Larsson songs]]\n\n{{2020s-single-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 song by Kygo, Zara Larsson and Tyga}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Like It Is\n| type       = single\n| cover      = Kygo - Like It Is.png\n| alt        =\n| artist     = [[Kygo]], [[Zara Larsson]] and [[Tyga]]\n| album      = Golden Hour\n| released   = {{start date|2020|03|27|df=y}}\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =\n| genre      = [[Tropical house]]<ref name=\"DA Review\"/>\n| length     = 3:03\n| label      = [[Sony Music]]\n| writer   =\n* [[Kygo|Kyrre G\u00f8rvell-Dahll]]\n* [[Zara Larsson]]\n* [[Tyga|Michael Stevenson]]\n* [[Dua Lipa]]\n* [[Ritual (electronic band)|Gerard O'Connell]]\n* [[Nick Hodgson]]\n* Patrick Martin\n| producer   =\n* Kygo\n* Petey Martin\n| chronology = [[Kygo]]\n| prev_title = [[Forever Yours (Tribute)]]\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| next_title = [[I'll Wait (Kygo and Sasha Sloan song)|I'll Wait]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Zara Larsson]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Invisible\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| title      = Like It Is\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Tyga]]\n| type       = single\n| prev_title = Contact\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| title      = Like It Is\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}{{External music video|{{YouTube|TOamHghGCfg|\"Like It Is\"}}\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Like It Is'''\" is a song by Norwegian DJ [[Kygo]], Swedish singer [[Zara Larsson]] and American rapper [[Tyga]]. It was released through [[Sony Music]] on 27 March 2020 as the lead single from Kygo's upcoming third studio album ''Golden Hour''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7908458/kygo-announces-new-single-like-it-is-featuring-zara-larsson-tyga|title=Kygo Announces New Single \"Like It Is\" Featuring Zara Larsson & Tyga|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|last=Wass|first=Mike|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nKygo announced on social media on 24 March 2020 that his third studio album was finished, and that the lead single would be out on Friday of that week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/9341792/kygo-announces-golden-hour-single-new-album|title=Kygo Is Back! The Producer Announces New Album Title & A Single Coming This Week|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Bain|first=Katie|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> Kygo also talked about spending time at home due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and \"staying positive in these tough times\"; ''[[Dancing Astronaut]]'' felt that Kygo's announcement came at a time when those in self-quarantine are \"hoping to bring some light during these dark quarantine days\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/kygo-announces-his-third-album-is-complete-first-single-to-be-released-this-friday/|title=Kygo announces his third album is complete\u2014first single to be released this Friday|website=Dancing Astronaut|last=Stack|first=Chris|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nFarrell Sweeney of ''[[Dancing Astronaut]]'' wrote that the song features \"enamoring vocals by Larsson, immediately pulling the listener into the catchy commercial fabric\" of the song. Sweeney also felt that Tyga's rap verse after the first drop was \"surprising\" and gave the song an \"unexpected twist\".<ref name=\"DA Review\">{{cite web|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/kygo-taps-zara-larsson-and-tyga-for-first-single-from-forthcoming-album/|title=Kygo taps Zara Larsson and Tyga for first single from forthcoming album|website=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|last=Sweeney|first=Farrell|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe video was released on 27 March 2020, and features Larsson and Tyga in an apartment building. It was called an \"artistic and colorful visual accompaniment\" by Sweeney.<ref name=\"DA Review\"/>\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|37|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|7|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|8|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|46|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=13&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 13, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 39\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Estonia ([[Eesti Tipp-40]])<ref name=\"estonianchart\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekspress.delfi.ee/areen/eesti-tipp-40-muusikas-dua-lipa-keeras-the-weekndil-kaela-kahekorra?id=89479383|title=EESTI TIPP-40 MUUSIKAS: Dua Lipa keeras The Weekndil kaela kahekorra|language=Estonian|last=Nestor|first=Siim|website=[[Eesti Ekspress]]|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 33\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|20|artist=Kygo,Zara Larsson,Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref name=\"frenchchart\">{{cite web|url=https://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 14, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 167\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|41|songid=1973243|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=3 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarysingle|17|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Hungarystream|28|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland4|25|date=20200417|rowheader=true|accessdate=18 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Lithuania ([[AGATA (organization)|AGATA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.agata.lt/lt/naujienos/savaites-klausomiausi-2020w14/|title=2020 14-os savait\u0117s klausomiausi (TOP 100)|publisher=[[AGATA (organization)|AGATA]]|language=Lithuanian|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 34\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|56|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand Hot Singles ([[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4841|title=NZ Hot Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Norway ([[VG-lista]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vglista.no/topplister/topp-20-single-2020-14/|title=VG-lista \u2013 Topp 20 Single uke 14, 2020|publisher=[[VG-lista]]|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 3\n|-\n{{single chart|Portugal|140|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|23|date=20200403|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Slovakdigital|48|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Sweden ([[Sverigetopplistan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/41?dspy=2020&dspp=14|title=Veckolista Singlar, vecka 14|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 4\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|9|artist=Kygo, Zara Larsson & Tyga|song=Like It Is|rowheader=true|accessdate=5 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|49|date=20200403|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardbubbling100|13|artist=Kygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboarddanceelectronic|5|artist=Kygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 April 2020}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kygo}}\n{{Zara Larsson}}\n{{Tyga}}\n\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Kygo songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kygo]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Dua Lipa]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Zara Larsson]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tyga]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Nick Hodgson]]\n[[Category:Tyga songs]]\n[[Category:Zara Larsson songs]]\n\n{{2020s-single-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lk95", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Like_It_Is_(song)"}
{"title_page": "List of We Bare Bears characters", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|date=December 2017}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2018}}\n}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''We Bare Bears'' characters}}\n\nThe American [[List of animated television series|animated television series]] ''[[We Bare Bears]]'' features a cast created by [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]. The series focuses on three bears who try to navigate the human world and make friends. The Bears are the loud and adventurous Grizz (voiced by [[Eric Edelstein]]), the kind, yet nervous Panda (voiced by [[Bobby Moynihan]]) and the quiet and mysterious Ice Bear (voiced by [[Demetri Martin]]). Despite their social ineptitude, they manage to meet a wide variety of characters who make recurring appearances on the show with some also making single appearances. Among them include the Korean American prodigy Chloe Park (voiced by [[Charlyne Yi]]), the selfish and angry Nom Nom (voiced by [[Patton Oswalt]]), the socially inept Bigfoot Charlie (voiced by [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]]) and the tough and determined Ranger Tabes (voiced by [[Cameron Esposito]]).\n\n==Main characters==\n===Grizzly===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Grizzly\n| series             = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| first              = \"We Bare Bears\" (Pilot)<br>\"Our Stuff\" <br>(Actual)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = [[Eric Edelstein]] <br>(Original)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Grizzly/|title=Voice of Grizzly|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref><br>[[Sam Lavagnino]] <br>(Young)\n| lbl1               = \n| data1              = \n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = Grizz\n| alias              = \n| species            = [[Grizzly bear]]\n| gender             = [[Male]]\n| color              = #804000\n}}\nGrizzly ('''nickname''' \"Grizz\") is a [[grizzly bear]]. The oldest and the de facto leader of the brothers, Grizz is a fun-loving bear who tends to get the others into random situations. Grizz is paradoxically highly sociable yet socially inept. Despite this, he is constantly wanting to meet new people and tries to befriend everyone he comes across. As a baby, he was rescued by a team of firemen who prevented him from falling off a tree-top during a storm (as such, he has a phobia of being in trees, which he states in \u201cPaperboyz\u201d). Afterward, he was adopted by a studio and starred in a Canadian sitcom called ''Family Troubles'' of which he was the star and known for his catchphrase \"That's not what I ordered!\" The show added a new character named Cousin Lorenzo whom Grizz immediately disliked. After winning in a race against him, Grizz suddenly realized that his fake family never offered true happiness or love and decided to leave the show to search for a family of his own, turning down fame and fortune in the process. It seems that he was younger than in most baby bear episodes according to the flashback pictures in \"Burrito.\" It was mentioned by Ice Bear that Grizz writes poems in English, as well as being a DJ and a beatboxer. He also possesses an alter ego as '''Crowbar Jones''' who is the star of a series of cheesy homemade action movies. Despite Grizz's desire to be loved by everyone, he still puts his brothers first and foremost and can't bear to be separated from them. He has a strange [[Love\u2013hate relationship|love-hate relationship]] with Nom Nom, whom he looks up to due to his popularity, yet acknowledges that he can be mean and sometimes untrustworthy. He also has an odd relationship with Ranger Tabes who usually calls on him to assist her with the Poppy Rangers, most likely due to the fact that since he is a grizzly bear and in theory, it makes sense that he would know a lot about nature, though it has shown that this is not the case. In the episode \"Bunnies\", Grizz is shown to be capable of speaking to other animals as most of them, who display self-awareness and occasional human behavior, aren't able to speak English.\n{{-}}\n\n===Panda===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Panda\n| series             = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| first              = \"We Bare Bears\" (Pilot)<br>\"Our Stuff\" <br>(Actual)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = [[Bobby Moynihan]] <br>(Original)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Panda/|title=Voice of Panda|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref><br>Duncan Joiner<br>(Young)<br>Max Mitchell <br>(Young){{efn|name=\"joinermitchell|Joiner and Mitchell interchange voices.}}\n| lbl1               = \n| data1              = \n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = Pan Pan\n| alias              = \n| species            = [[Giant panda]]\n| gender             = [[Male]]\n| color              = Black\n}}\nPanda is a [[giant panda]]. He is the middle brother and is nicknamed Pan-Pan by Grizz. He is tender-hearted and gets embarrassed or anxious easily. It is revealed in \"Panda 2\" that Panda once lived in a controlled panda enclosure near [[Shanghai|Shanghai, China]]. A stuffed panda plush doll was dropped into his enclosure by one of the staff who noticed his loneliness and Panda befriended it by giving it a personality, which is mainly Panda voicing his deeper inner thoughts through the doll. Panda used the doll as a method of convincing himself to look through a window on the wall of the observatory, something he has always been curious about but never attempted to actually see. After using the doll to prop himself up, he finds a television set and becomes entranced by the moving pictures, and [[Anime]], which is most likely how Panda came to appreciate it later in his life. In an effort to show his \"friend\" the Television, Panda escapes the Habitat through a food chute but after being discovered he jumps out the window of the laboratory and hides in a [[bamboo]] delivery truck, which brings him into downtown Shanghai. Panda has a lot less self-confidence than his brothers. He is good with technology and uses that skill on online social media and dating sites, with which he finds little to no success. He is also the one who \"falls in love\" the most quickly. Often several times to court several human girls, most notably Lucy the produce girl who has platonic feelings for him. Panda also owns a [[Comfort object|security pillow]] in the form of '''Miki-Chan''', a pillow with a picture of an anime schoolgirl (or dakimakura) on it who he pretends to be his actual girlfriend. He is the most creative of the brothers, having written songs in \"[[YouTube|Everyone's Tube]]\", and undoubtedly the \"cutest\" as settled in \"Panda's Sneeze.\" Panda is a [[Ovo vegetarianism|ovo-vegeterian]] and has severe allergies to peanuts and cats. It has been revealed that Panda likes [[Anime]] and enjoys other things related to Japanese culture. He can be seen eating [[Ramen]] in multiple episodes, and in \"Hibernation\" he is seen eating a snack similar to [[Pocky]]. Panda also attends community college where he majors in art as revealed in \"Panda's Art.\"\n{{-}}\n\n===Ice Bear===\n{{redirect|Ice Bear|the type of bear|Polar bear||Ice Bears (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Ice Bear\n| series             = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = ice bear \n| caption            = \n| first              = \"We Bare Bears\" (Pilot)<br>\"Our Stuff\"<br> (Actual)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = [[Demetri Martin]]<br>(Original)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Ice-Bear/|title=Voice of Ice Bear|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref><br>Max Mitchell <br>(Young)\n| lbl1               = \n| data1              = \n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = Ice\n| alias              = \n| species            = [[Polar bear]]\n| gender             = [[Male]]\n| color              = #FFFFFF\n}}\nIce Bear is a [[polar bear]]. He is the youngest brother and is usually called bro. Ice Bear is often rather stoic and rarely speaks. When he does, he speaks mostly in the third person and says his name first instead of I as shown in \u00a8The Audition\u00a8. It is revealed in \"Yuri and the Bear\" that Ice Bear was raised by a Russian man named Yuri after his mother was killed by poachers. This is how he learned to speak Russian, and because Yuri spoke exclusively in the third person, this is most likely how Ice Bear obtained the habit. He earned accommodation by learning to chop wood, cook salmon, read maps, study calculus, knit, play [[Uno (card game)|Uno]] with standard cards and speak Russian and English, but was cut adrift into the ocean when Yuri had to let him go to save him from the poachers, and the ice floated away from the mainland. He is multilingual, having been shown to speak Korean, French, Japanese (on \"Losing Ice\")and Russian fluently.  Ice Bear also is able to speak to pigeons in the episode \"Our Stuff.\" He is also a skilled chef, dancer, piano player, a novice at robotics, charade player (on \"My Clique\"; it was revealed on \"The Island\" that he learned to speak very late, and originally used his charades skills to communicate), welder, poet (which he writes in French), roller skater and a [[Mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] (cited as [[Brazilian jiu-jitsu]] on \"Chloe\", but his skill set is closer to [[Taekwondo]] and [[judo]] with skills in [[Nunchaku]], [[Shuriken]] and swords). Ice Bear is the most composed of the brothers, always maintaining an \"ice-cool attitude\" in even the most awkward and embarrassing of situations. As seen in \"Losing Ice\" and \"Coffee Cave\", his brothers often take him for granted and are unappreciative of all the cooking and cleaning he does, although they eventually realize the error of their ways. Ice Bear sleeps in the refrigerator with a fire ax which he can use with either hand. Of the three bears, he has the closest relationship with Chloe, almost acting as a quiet big brother to her.\n{{-}}\n\n==Recurring characters==\n===Chloe Park===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Chloe Park\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Chloe\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Charlyne Yi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Chloe/|title=Voice of Chloe|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref>\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name        = \n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = Human\n| gender           = Female\n}}\nChloe Park doesn't have many friends other than the bears and has a hard time relating to her much older peers. In \"My Clique,\" Chloe finally makes some friends with her college classmates, albeit with the help of the Bears. In the same episode, she is revealed to be [[Multilingualism|bilingual]]. Chloe devotes most of her time to studying in the hopes of having a secure future and becomes stressed when it seems like she is on the verge of failing as evidenced in \"The Library\" and \"Professor Lampwick\". Despite fully knowing that the bears mean well, their antics sometimes stress her too. At one point she was nearly driven insane by the Bears when they got sick in the episode \"Bear Flu\" due to them asking for things. Nevertheless, she adores them and will often rely on them for help. She has shown to be involved with their misadventures such as in \"The Demon\" and \"Road Trip\". She also has an interesting connection with Ice Bear due to his quiet persona meshed with her more open personality as seen in \"Chloe and Ice Bear\". Of the three bears, she is most often seen with him.\n\n===Nom Nom===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Nom Nom\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Viral Video\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Patton Oswalt]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Nom-Nom/|title=Voice of Nom Nom|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref>\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name         = \n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = [[Koala]]\n| gender           = Male\n}}\nNom Nom is a misanthropic self-hating [[koala]]. He is a famous internet star, known for his \"cute\" videos and the main antagonist during the two first seasons, starting a slow redemption from the third season onward. While he doesn't talk in any of his videos, Nom Nom often swears angrily towards everyone he comes in contact with, especially the bears. Grizzly imposes him enough to talk to him and admits that he liked his video, but Nom Nom is self-centered and more concerned with materialistic things, and is very selfish and lashes out at anyone who he doesn't like. One example being in \"The Nom Nom Show\" where he was unwilling to share the spotlight with the Bears, despite the positive reception they received. In \"Viral Video,\" Nom Nom says that he does not want any friends because he finds them unimportant and too loud, and proves his point by kicking Grizz out of his limo. His temper is so short, he lashes out at anyone who even slightly annoys him. In \"Anger Management\", it's revealed that Grizz's hugs genuinely calm him to the point of making him optimistic and friendly. He has further shown a more tolerant side. In \"Nom Nom's Entourage,\" he saves a picture of his time with the Bears and in \"Kyle,\" opened his home to another koala who claimed to be his brother. In \"Vacation\", he finally admits that Grizz is the closest thing to a friend he has. In \"Crowbar Jones: Origins\", Nom Nom is shown to be more tolerant of Grizz though he still finds him a nuisance.\n\n===Charlie===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Charlie\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Charlie\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]]<ref name=\"WBBCast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/we-bare-bears-gets-3rd-season-at-cartoon-network-940884|title='We Bare Bears' Gets 3rd Season at Cartoon Network|last=Greenho|first=Caitlin|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 25, 2016}}</ref>\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name         = \n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = [[Bigfoot]]\n| gender           = Male\n}}\nCharlie is a friendly [[bigfoot]] who wanders alone around the San Francisco woods until he meets the Bears in \"Charlie,\" where they agree to let him live in their cave for a little while via a website called CaveShare. While it is unknown how old he is, he is apparently more than a century old as he is shown living as far back as 1913 as seen in \"El Oso\". It is revealed that, due to his life of solitude, he is socially inept and doesn't know how to be a good friend. This results in him unintentionally causing havoc for the Bears whenever he hangs out with them. He is also constantly harassed by humans trying to get pictures of him, which results in him becoming [[Xenophobia|xenophobic]] towards them and developing a fear of cameras. He has on more than one occasion befriended someone other than the Bears. In \"El Oso\", he made friends with the titular character and in \"Rescue Ranger\", he mildly learns to put up with Tabes, but eventually accepts her as his friend in \"Charlie & Tabes\" after getting her name wrong numerous times (Tubes, Tebs, etc.). In \"Hurricane Hal\", his actual home is shown to be a broken-down car while in \"Christmas Parties\" he lives in a giant tree. In the episode \"Charlie Ball,\" we see that Charlie is extremely skilled at ball-handling and that his height makes him perfect for [[basketball]]. In \"Charlie's Big Foot,\" Charlie is revealed to have blue-colored blood and a very jointed body, mostly due to being harmed by the wilderness which he views as perfectly normal, and in \"Bubble\", it is revealed that his natural fur is actually gold colored making him look handsome and majestic. He also sees Panda as his best friend and usually tries to show off new discoveries and his \"decor\" to him over the other two. Besides Panda, he also is friends with a common snake as seen in \"Charlie and the Snake\".\n\n===Ranger Tabes===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Ranger Tabes\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Ranger Tabes\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Cameron Esposito]]<ref name=\"WBBCast\" />\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name         = Dana Tabes\n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = Human\n| gender           = Female\n}}\nRanger Dana Tabes is a [[National Park Service ranger|park ranger]]. She lives in a trailer-style mobile home located in the park where the Bears live. They first meet her in \"Ranger Tabes\" where she helps them locate a missing package. She is shown to be overly confident, persistent and even downright obsessive with wanting to help people. Her obsession is explored in \"Creature Mysteries\" where she tries to capture and prove Charlie's existence. In that same episode, it's revealed that her mother was also a park ranger and the one who inspired her to become one. Her obsession is also prominent in \"Poppy Rangers\" where she was willing to lead a team of girl scouts, called the Poppy Rangers, into a dangerous cave, against Grizzly's wishes. Despite her quirky personality, the Bears consider her as one of their closest friends and praise her to some extent as seen in \"Ranger Norm\". Out of all of them, Tabes seems to coerce with Grizz the most and usually has him around as an assistant to help in leading the Poppy Rangers. Based on how much she relies on him, they seem to have mutual respect for each for other. In \"Ranger Games\", it is revealed that she has a rival in the form of '''Ranger Zhao''' (voiced by [[Ming-Na Wen]]) who leads her own group of girl scouts called the Ivy Rangers. In \"Bear Squad\", Tabes is shown to possess deduction skills to the level of identifying animals and people by a limited amount of evidence. In the same episode, it is revealed that she is banned from doing any ranger work in the city. Over time, Tabes is shown to have calmed down a bit, though she still takes her job very seriously. She has even learned to be more surveillant with her duties and upon knowledge of Charlie's true existence has opted to watch and protect him from afar. By the end of \"Rescue Ranger\", she mildly becomes friends with Charlie and, like the Bears, decides to keep him a secret. Eventually, the two become good friends after he helps her finds her dog Kirk in \"Tabes & Charlie\".\n\n===Lucy===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Lucy\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Panda's Date\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Ellie Kemper]]<ref name=\"WBBCast\" />\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name         = \n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = Human\n| gender           = Female\n}}\nLucy is a friend to the Bears and runs a produce delivery service called ''Lucy's Produce''. She first appears in \"Panda's Date\" where she takes an immediate liking to the Bears and their goofy personalities. Panda quickly (as usual) develops a crush on her, but she seems to be unaware of his feelings. She finally returns in season 3 episode, \"Lucy's Brother\" where it is revealed that she delivers fruit to the Bears every Friday. In that same episode, she is shown to have a younger brother named Clifford whom she cares for and worries over immensely. She is also shown to be a terrible dancer, something which Panda was nervous telling her about, but she learns to accept after he realizes how important it is, to be honest, and faithful to her. Despite being oblivious to Panda's feelings for her, the two share a mutual friendship. In \"The Limo\", Lucy begins dating '''Kale''' (voiced by [[Omid Abtahi]]) which upsets Panda, but he ultimately accepts as her happiness is what matters.\n{{-}}\n\n==Minor characters==\n===Pigeon Cartel===\nThe Pigeon Cartel is composed of pigeons who are actually an underground illegal trading ring. They are the closest thing to arch-enemies the Bears have and first appeared in \"Our Stuff\". They stole the Bears' items, which included Grizz's wallet, Panda's cell phone and Ice Bear's ninja stars, along with a wide variety of other expensive and important items around the city. The Bears unintentionally landed in their hideout where the cartel or at least a subgroup of them were arrested. In \"Pigeons\", they are revealed to have a member in their ranks named '''Brenda''' whom Grizz ends up befriending. Brenda actually tricks Grizz into helping her free her gang from prison, or rather the pigeon coup inside the prison, she ultimately has a change of heart due to Grizz's kindness.\n\n===Chloe's Family===\n* '''Mr. Park''' (voiced by Jinkoo Jeong) is Chloe's father. He was initially reserved about Chloe hanging out with the bears, but warms up to their presence in \"Slumber Party\". He is bilingual.\n* '''Mrs. Park''' (voiced by [[Niki Yang]]) is Chloe's mother. She is very supportive of Chloe's friendship with the bears as evidenced when she makes sandwiches for them in \"Chloe and Ice Bear\". She is bilingual.\n* '''Jon Park''' (voiced by Bert Youn) is Chloe's cousin. He appeared in \"Christmas Parties\" where is shown to be rather cocky and doesn't get along with Chloe very well. He has a habit of pranking her every chance he gets and always gets away with it.\n\n===Farmer===\nFarmer (voiced by Kyler Spears) is Nom Nom's personal [[bodyguard]]. He was initially known as '''Bodyguard #1''' due to his primary task of protecting Nom Nom who in turn didn't think much of him. However, this all changed in the episode \"Kyle\" where it is shown that Farmer genuinely cares for Nom Nom's security when he suspected that the titular koala was trying to scam Nom Nom. After rescuing his employer, Nom Nom became more aware of him and asked for his real name, calling him Farmer from that point on.\n\n===Rangers===\n*'''Kirk''' is a dog that Tabes was given as a Christmas present by the Bears in \"Christmas Parties\". In \"Lunch with Tabes,\" he is shown to be rather clever and mischievous. In \"Tabes & Charlie\", he is revealed to have fathered three pups with a wolf.\n* '''Ranger Martinez''' (voiced by [[Keith Ferguson (voice actor)|Keith Ferguson]]) is Tabes' partner. He has been a park ranger since Tabes was a child and was initially her mother's partner. In his old age, he is always prone to sleep and is shown to be rather laid back. He is also very friendly with the Bears.\n* '''Poppy Rangers''' are the team of girl scouts that Ranger Tabes, and to a certain extent Grizz, lead in a variety of tasks and activities. Their ranks include '''Diaz''' (voiced by Marissa Soto), a \"curious and witty\" girl who aspires to be a [[biologist]]; '''Parker''' (voiced by Danity Harris), a \"quiet and confidant\" girl who aspires to be an [[Aerospace engineering|aeronautical engineer]]; '''Murphy''' (voiced by Stella Balick-Karrer), a \"cheerful and patient\" girl who aspires to be a [[geologist]]; '''Nguyen''' (voiced by Audrey Huynh) another \"quiet and confident\" girl who aspires to be a [[principal dancer]] and '''Wallace''' (voiced by Cate Gragnani) an eye-patch wearing \"fearless...born leader\" who aspires to be a park ranger like Tabes. It is unknown whether Wallace has only injured her eye or lost it, only stating that \"it was worth it\". The girls unanimously trust Tabes' leadership and advice, but also adore Grizz whom they affectionately call 'Bear Guy', even though they are well aware of his flaws such as in \"Ranger Games\" and even admit that he is terrible at leading as seen in \"Lord of the Poppies\". In the former episode, their rivals, the '''Ivy Rangers''', as well as Wallace's younger sister '''Chuck Wallace''' are introduced.\n\n===Clifford===\nClifford (voiced by Hudson West) is Lucy's younger brother. He has many allergies and has trouble socializing with others. He constantly wanders off and is very shy. He starts to like Panda once he is considered a friend. He is also very defensive of his sister, seen as he is aware that many boys use him as an attempt to get close to her and gets mad at Panda for doing so. Fortunately, he and Panda reconcile and consider each other close friends.\n\n===Darrell===\nDarrell Saragosa (voiced by [[Mel Rodriguez]]) a 35-year-old man, is a friend to the Bears and owns a [[mousepad]] store called ''Super Rad Mousepads''. He first appears in \"Losing Ice\" where he answers a want ad from Grizz and Panda asking for a replacement for the missing Ice Bear. He happily takes the job, despite the harsh conditions, and later makes them realize their error in taking Ice Bear for granted. He lives with his grandma, Emma, who apparently does most of his cooking. He returns in \"Bear Lift\" where the Bears help his fledgling business. It's also shown that in his youth his store was once booming and brought people together, but over time it began to wear away. By the end, the Bears help bring the store back due to its 'retro' appeal. In \"Best Bears\" Darrell marries '''Sofia''' (voiced by Brigitte Kali Canales), a [[hang gliding]] instructor and [[fashion design]]er who thinks that he and the Bears are cool.\n\n===Yana===\nYana (voiced by [[Margarita Levieva]]) is a Russian woman with dark connections to Ice Bear. She is an aggressive woman with a sentimental side to her as well. She and Ice Bear have known each other for a long time and have been on missions together for unknown reasons. Yana first appeared in \"Icy Nights\" where she briefly helped Ice Bear look for his Roomba. She returns in \"Icy Nights II\" where she is kidnapped by Barry, a tech genius who is after the Roomba. At the end of the episode, it's revealed that Yana's father is Yuri, the same man who raised Ice Bear. It's unknown whether Yuri is still in contact with her or knows that she's still alive.\n\n===Barry===\nBarry Charles (voiced by [[Kevin McHale (actor)|Kevin McHale]]) is a technical expert and Ice Bear's nemesis. He leads a gang of techies and is involved in illegal activities. His main goal is to steal Ice Bear's Roomba due to the technical specifications it possesses. The reason for doing this is so that he can earn the approval of his father, something that is a sore spot for him.\n\n===Marie===\nMarie (voiced by Edi Patterson) is a web show host that the Bears occasionally watch. She hosts the show ''Mornings with Marie'' off from the website ''[[YouTube|Everyone's Tube]]''. She tends to report on all the latest crazes and current things usually from the internet such as Nom Nom and Panda's sudden popularity like in \"Panda's Sneeze\". Marie also hosts the ''Cute-Off'', a competition where two animals from viral videos participate.\n\n===The Bros===\nThe Bros are the human doppelgangers to the Bears. They first appeared in \"Panda's Friend\". They fittingly display qualities similar to, but also superior to the actual bears.\n* '''Tom''' (voiced by Bert Youn) is Panda's counterpart. He is a small, presumably Asian, man, who wears glasses and typically wears a black hoodie with a white stripe going through it so as to resemble a panda. He, just like Panda, loves Korean dramas and anime and is apparently 97% similar. He becomes way too attached to Panda and kidnaps him from his home and moves him into his apartment. When he realizes how obsessive he has become he leaves (or rather falls) and meets his other two roommates Griff and Isaac. He is much more stable with the two and in \"Bro Brawl\" implies that they are his only real family as well. In that same episode, he states that he has a girlfriend.\n* '''Griff''' (voiced by Eric Edelstein in \"Panda's Friend\" and later by Faruq Tauheed) is Grizz's counterpart. Griff is a \"renegade\" cop, later revealed to be a mall cop, who loves his job and is capable of helping people, as opposed to Grizz who has no job and, while helpful, is socially inept. He is a well built African-American man who usually wears a blue shirt. He seems to care a lot about his roommates and in his first appearance was nervous about losing his home for not meeting the roommate quota until Tom literally dropped in. In \"The Mall\", he is shown to be very friendly with Grizz.\n* '''Isaac''' (voiced by Demetri Martin) is Ice Bear's counterpart. Isaac is a \"five-star chef\" who, much like Ice Bear, is tall and quiet. He wears a white hoodie with the hood always over his head and his blonde bangs hanging out. When he speaks he follows Ice Bear's speech mannerisms by talking in the third person. He sleeps in a walk-in closet, like how Ice Bear sleeps in a fridge and also seems to possess many outlandish abilities. In \"Bro Brawl\" he one up Ice Bear due to not having any hair in his food. In \"The Mall\", he and Ice Bear seem to view each other as rivals.\n\n===Captain Craboo===\nCaptain Craboo is the Bears' pet crab whom they adopted in the episode \"Emergency\". He actually came from the supermarket which Grizz went to buy food and immediately fell in love with the crab. Unfortunately, it pinches onto Ice Bear's ear causing him to become catatonic and deranged. Grizz and Panda eventually get Craboo off of Ice Bear and resort to giving him tiny mitts so that he doesn't pinch Ice Bear again. He returns in \"Captain Craboo\" where it is revealed that he has been gone for quite some time and that Ice Bear still has not forgiven him. However, the two later make up. In that same episode, Craboo attacks Nom Nom, making him a wanted fugitive. By the end of the episode, Craboo solemnly leaves the Bears before they release him into the ocean, especially Ice Bear, who took his departure the hardest.\n\n===The Mailman===\nThe Mailman (voiced by Keith Ferguson) is a friendly [[Postal worker|mailman]] that occasionally visits the Bears. He first appears in \"Nom Nom\" where he delivers a toy helicopter to the Bears. He falls into a pit where Ice Bear was trapped by Nom Nom. He shows that he doesn't mind the situation and also didn't seem to mind being left there. He returns in \"Crowbar Jones\" where he was invited to see the titular movie that Grizz had made. He was easily impressed by it and based on his reactions, simply wishes to have friends. In \"Citizen Tabes,\" he was also impressed with Tabes' packaging to the point that he was willing to listen to her ramble about how she did it. In \"I, Butler\", he was interested in playing basketball with the bears even though he creepily appeared from behind their bushes.\n\n===Mad Scientist===\nMad Scientist (voiced by [[Jason Mantzoukas]]) is an unnamed scientist who is constantly plotting against the government. He first appears in \"Grizz Helps\" where Grizz answers a want ad for someone to aid him in traveling back in time. He was going to use a chicken named Mark as a test subject and Grizz had to rescue him for its owner. The scientist reappeared in \"Summer Love\" with a pelican assistant named Gary and tried to use a body swapping machine on Panda. He revealed that he once had a girlfriend named Amelia who joined the space program, implying one of the reasons he kept conspiring against the government.\n\n===Ralph===\nRalph (voiced by [[John DiMaggio]]) is a [[yeti]] who enjoys playing cruel pranks on humans and animals. He first appears in \"Ralph\" where Charlie befriends him due to being a creature just like him, despite the Bears gaining distrust of Ralph due to his mean nature. He ends up abandoning Charlie when the latter refuses to let a group of humans fall off a bridge as part of a prank, considering him a \"snooze-fest\". He appears again in \"Ice Cave\" where he takes over the Bears' cave and freezes its interior, ruling it like a king. He usually puts Charlie down due to his lanky body and pushes over personality, but Charlie stands up to him and puts Ralph in his place.\n\n===Dr. Clark===\nDr. Clark (voiced by Avery Kidd Waddell) is a medical nurse and Nom Nom's personal doctor. He first appeared in \"Charlie's Big Foot\" where he treated Charlie's foot after it broke. He is shown to have a very unusual [[Doctor\u2013patient relationship|bedside manner]] in that he has a very lethargic and slightly disinterested way of speaking. However, he is shown to take his job seriously and looked aghast at seeing Charlie's blood. He returned in \"Vacation\" where he acted as Nom Nom's personal doctor. His diagnosis was that he was stressed and prescribed that he take a vacation with Grizz acting as his coach. Once again, Dr. Clark delivered all of this in a lethargic disinterested attitude. In \"Braces\", he is revealed to also serve as a dentist and possesses numerous doctoral degrees.\n\n==Guest characters==\n===Paul and Annie===\nPaul (voiced by [[Lou Ferrigno]]) and Annie (voiced by [[Grey DeLisle|Grey Griffin]]) are a married couple that appeared in \"Yard Sale\". Annie is an average looking red-haired woman who was heavily [[Pregnancy|pregnant]]. She sold a box of free things to the Bears at a yard sale she had set up. The things in question were large foam toy fists (which Grizz begins wearing only for them to get stuck to his paws) her husband Paul's phone (which Panda mistakenly takes and begins sending texts unknowingly to Annie) and a pregnancy workout DVD (which Ice Bear begins watching and using to get in better shape). Paul, who resembles a large well-built man, is offended at Panda using his phone and possessively threatens him, but becomes nervous and faints when Annie goes into labor. The Bears band together to get Annie and Paul to the hospital where she successfully gives birth to a baby boy that somehow manages to removes the fake hands off of Grizz, much to everyone's surprise since he had difficulty removing them before.\n\n===Professor Lampwick===\nProfessor Lampwick (voiced by [[Malcolm McDowell]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Professor-Lampwick/|title=Voice of Professor Lampwick|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 22, 2017}}</ref> is Chloe's science professor at the university and he appeared in his self-titled episode. Lampwick is a tall, lean older man with a sinister and stern personality. He has a notorious reputation for being a difficult professor who refuses second chances with his students. Chloe gets so intimidated by him that she fails her course causing her much grief. However, the Bears decide to kidnap him and bring him back to the cave in an effort to force him to give Chloe a second chance. Lampwick proves to be crafty as he turns the Bears against one another, forcing Chloe to step up and demand a second chance, which he grants. When Chloe passes, Lampwick reveals that he untied his own bonds and was just testing her, admitting that she wasn't the first student to \"kidnap [him] over a grade.\" He briefly returns in \"Hurricane Hal\" where he is shown to have an omniscient presence as he was capable of explaining exactly what each of the Bears was doing and apparently is aware of who Charlie is.\n\n===Andy Bangs===\nAndrew \"Andy\" Bangs (voiced by [[Bo Burnham]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Andy-Bangs/|title=Voice of Andy Bangs|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 22, 2017}}</ref> is a child internet star and Nom Nom's main rival who appeared in \"Nom Nom's Entourage\". Andy's name is a pun on the fact that his videos consist mostly of him popping out of places and shouting \"Bang!\" and that he has [[Hair coloring|dyed]] [[Bangs (hair)|bangs]]. He takes great pleasure in humiliating and outsmarting Nom Nom using his trademark surprise gimmick. One thing he has over Nom Nom, is the fact that he is constantly surrounded by his entourage, which Nom Nom lacks forcing him to hire the Bears. Nom eventually manages to get back at Andy by surprising him with his signature \"Bang!\".\n\n===Karla and Dave===\nKarla (voiced by [[Felicia Day]]) and Dave (voiced by [[Jake Johnson]]) are a pair of castaways that the baby Bears encounter in \"The Island\". The Bears are rescued from quicksand by Karla and Dave who have been shipwrecked on the island for some unspecified amount of time. All that is known is that they came separately. Karla mostly misses her sister whom she loves very much and forms a motherly bond with the baby Bears, while Dave displays a slightly disinterested attitude. It eventually becomes clear, that Dave has been misleading Karla and the Bears and that he wants Karla to stay with him alone. The Bears rescue Karla from Dave and escape on an inflatable raft they found, leaving Dave all alone. Karla is rescued by a passing ship, but the Bears float on until they end up in [[Japan]].\n\n===Yuri===\nYuri (voiced by [[Darin De Paul]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Yuri/|title=Voice of Yuri|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 22, 2017}}</ref> is an old Russian man who lived out in the arctic as a [[hermit]] [[Survivalism|survivalist]], until he met baby Ice Bear in the episode \"Yuri and the Bear\". A tall, large bearded man who much like Ice Bear, had a tendency to speak in the third person, Yuri lived in a life of solitude after losing his family to some unknown causes. He took Ice Bear under his wing, after some reluctance, and taught him everything that he knew. They were confronted by a hunter, who is implied to have killed Ice Bear's family, and Yuri is forced to cut Ice Bear away from land to save him. In \"Icy Nights II\", it is revealed that Yuri is Yana's father.\n\n===Wyatt===\nWyatt (voiced by [[Ron Funches]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bubbleblabber.com/review-we-bare-bears-road-trip/|title=Review: We Bare Bears \"Road Trip\"|last=Schwarz|first=John|website=Bubble Babbler|date=August 7, 2017|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref> is the overly kind leader of a [[Outlaw motorcycle club|bike gang]] in \"Road Trip\". Wyatt is a random individual that Chloe and the Bears encounter while on their way to see the meteor shower. He displays a slightly lethargic, yet kind and joking attitude that clicks with Grizz, Panda, and Chloe but annoys Ice Bear. He claims that he lost his bike gang and is allowed to ride with them, much to Ice Bear's chagrin. Eventually, Ice Bear manages to take off without him only to have the car run out of gas. Wyatt shows up with his gang and they offer to share their gas with them. Later on, he joins Chloe and the Bears in watching the meteor shower.\n\n===Warren and Faye===\nWarren (voiced by [[Robert Clotworthy]]) and Faye (voiced by [[Frances Conroy]]) are a friendly elderly couple who live in a [[Recreational vehicle|RV]] in the woods somewhere near where the Bears live. They appear in the episode \"Neighbors\" and are depicted as an overly kind couple who immediately take joy in conversing with the Bears. While Panda and Ice Bear find them pleasant, Grizz finds them uncomfortably nice as the two are shown touching and examining the Bears. The two begin taking pictures of the Bears going about their day and it is revealed that they keep numerous knives and other cutting instruments, giving the impression that they plan on cutting up or eating the Bears. However, it is revealed that the two are wood carving fanatics and simply wanted the Bears to model for them for their hobby. They forgive the Bears for their snooping. Warren and Fay are named after [[Warren Beatty]] and [[Faye Dunaway]].\n\n===Esteller===\nEsteller (voiced by [[Estelle (musician)|Estelle]]) is a famous pop song singer who Panda and Tom are huge fans of. She appears in the episode \"The Mall\" where she arrives at the titular location to personally sign autographs for her fans, whom she affectionately refers to as her \"starlings\". Esteller is moved by Panda and Tom's willingness to let their shirts be ruined so that they can get a chance to meet her in person. She thanks them and gives them new signed shirts while politely berating the other fans that tried to ruin their shirts to begin with by telling them, \"Don't be jerks.\" Estelle sings the series' theme song and had previously appeared as herself in the episode \"More Everyone's Tube\" where she sang the full version.\n\n===Charles Barkley===\n[[Charles Barkley]] as himself appears in the episode \"Baby Bears Can't Jump\". He is a famous basketball player that the bears admire when they find a basketball card about him.\n\n===T-Pain===\n[[T-Pain]] as himself appears in the episode \"The Limo\". He is a rapper. It is revealed that he watched Grizz's Crowbar Jones series. Panda is a fan of the rapper.\n\n===Monsta X===\n[[Monsta X]] as themselves appear in the episode \"Panda's Birthday\". The group comprises seven members: Shownu, Wonho, Minhyuk, Kihyun, Hyungwon, Jooheon, and I.M. Panda is a fan of the K-pop group, but Grizz and Ice Bear are not, since they mixed up the group with another metal rock group called Monta S.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cartoon Network}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:We Bare Bears}}\n[[Category: Cartoon Network Studios series and characters]]\n[[Category:Lists of characters in American television animation]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2015|*, We Bare Bears]]\n[[Category: Fictional polar bears]]\n[[Category:Fictional pandas]]\n[[Category:We Bare Bears]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|date=December 2017}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2018}}\n}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''We Bare Bears'' characters}}\n\nThe American [[List of animated television series|animated television series]] ''[[We Bare Bears]]'' features a cast created by [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]. The series focuses on three bears who try to navigate the human world and make friends. The Bears are the loud and adventurous Grizz (voiced by [[Eric Edelstein]]), the kind, yet nervous Panda (voiced by [[Bobby Moynihan]]) and the quiet and mysterious Ice Bear (voiced by [[Demetri Martin]]). Despite their social ineptitude, they manage to meet a wide variety of characters who make recurring appearances on the show with some also making single appearances. Among them include the Korean American prodigy Chloe Park (voiced by [[Charlyne Yi]]), the selfish and angry Nom Nom (voiced by [[Patton Oswalt]]), the socially inept Bigfoot Charlie (voiced by [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]]) and the tough and determined Ranger Tabes (voiced by [[Cameron Esposito]]).\n\n==Main characters==\n===Grizzly===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Grizzly\n| series             = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| first              = \"We Bare Bears\" (Pilot)<br>\"Our Stuff\" <br>(Actual)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = [[Eric Edelstein]] <br>(Original)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Grizzly/|title=Voice of Grizzly|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref><br>[[Sam Lavagnino]] <br>(Young)\n| lbl1               = \n| data1              = \n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = Grizz\n| alias              = \n| species            = [[Grizzly bear]]\n| gender             = [[Male]]\n| color              = #804000\n}}\nGrizzly ('''nickname''' \"Grizz\") is a [[grizzly bear]]. The oldest and the de facto leader of the brothers, Grizz is a fun-loving bear who tends to get the others into random situations. Grizz is paradoxically highly sociable yet socially inept. Despite this, he is constantly wanting to meet new people and tries to befriend everyone he comes across. As a baby, he was rescued by a team of firemen who prevented him from falling off a tree-top during a storm (as such, he has a phobia of being in trees, which he states in \u201cPaperboyz\u201d). Afterward, he was adopted by a studio and starred in a Canadian sitcom called ''Family Troubles'' of which he was the star and known for his catchphrase \"That's not what I ordered!\" The show added a new character named Cousin Lorenzo whom Grizz immediately disliked. After winning in a race against him, Grizz suddenly realized that his fake family never offered true happiness or love and decided to leave the show to search for a family of his own, turning down fame and fortune in the process. It seems that he was younger than in most baby bear episodes according to the flashback pictures in \"Burrito.\" It was mentioned by Ice Bear that Grizz writes poems in English, as well as being a DJ and a beatboxer. He also possesses an alter ego as '''Crowbar Jones''' who is the star of a series of cheesy homemade action movies. Despite Grizz's desire to be loved by everyone, he still puts his brothers first and foremost and can't bear to be separated from them. He has a strange [[Love\u2013hate relationship|love-hate relationship]] with Nom Nom, whom he looks up to due to his popularity, yet acknowledges that he can be mean and sometimes untrustworthy. He also has an odd relationship with Ranger Tabes who usually calls on him to assist her with the Poppy Rangers, most likely due to the fact that since he is a grizzly bear and in theory, it makes sense that he would know a lot about nature, though it has shown that this is not the case. In the episode \"Bunnies\", Grizz is shown to be capable of speaking to other animals as most of them, who display self-awareness and occasional human behavior, aren't able to speak English.\n{{-}}\n\n===Panda===\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Panda\n| series             = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| first              = \"We Bare Bears\" (Pilot)<br>\"Our Stuff\" <br>(Actual)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = [[Bobby Moynihan]] <br>(Original)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Panda/|title=Voice of Panda|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref><br>Duncan Joiner<br>(Young)<br>Max Mitchell <br>(Young){{efn|name=\"joinermitchell|Joiner and Mitchell interchange voices.}}\n| lbl1               = \n| data1              = \n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = Pan Pan\n| alias              = \n| species            = [[Giant panda]]\n| gender             = [[Male]]\n| color              = Black\n}}\nPanda is a [[giant panda]]. He is the middle brother and is nicknamed Pan-Pan by Grizz. He is tender-hearted and gets embarrassed or anxious easily. It is revealed in \"Panda 2\" that Panda once lived in a controlled panda enclosure near [[Shanghai|Shanghai, China]]. A stuffed panda plush doll was dropped into his enclosure by one of the staff who noticed his loneliness and Panda befriended it by giving it a personality, which is mainly Panda voicing his deeper inner thoughts through the doll. Panda used the doll as a method of convincing himself to look through a window on the wall of the observatory, something he has always been curious about but never attempted to actually see. After using the doll to prop himself up, he finds a television set and becomes entranced by the moving pictures, and [[Anime]], which is most likely how Panda came to appreciate it later in his life. In an effort to show his \"friend\" the Television, Panda escapes the Habitat through a food chute but after being discovered he jumps out the window of the laboratory and hides in a [[bamboo]] delivery truck, which brings him into downtown Shanghai. Panda has a lot less self-confidence than his brothers. He is good with technology and uses that skill on online social media and dating sites, with which he finds little to no success. He is also the one who \"falls in love\" the most quickly. Often several times to court several human girls, most notably Lucy the produce girl who has platonic feelings for him. Panda also owns a [[Comfort object|security pillow]] in the form of '''Miki-Chan''', a pillow with a picture of an anime schoolgirl (or dakimakura) on it who he pretends to be his actual girlfriend. He is the most creative of the brothers, having written songs in \"[[YouTube|Everyone's Tube]]\", and undoubtedly the \"cutest\" as settled in \"Panda's Sneeze.\" Panda is a [[Ovo vegetarianism|ovo-vegeterian]] and has severe allergies to peanuts and cats. It has been revealed that Panda likes [[Anime]] and enjoys other things related to Japanese culture. He can be seen eating [[Ramen]] in multiple episodes, and in \"Hibernation\" he is seen eating a snack similar to [[Pocky]]. Panda also attends community college where he majors in art as revealed in \"Panda's Art.\"\n{{-}}\n\n===Ice Bear===\n{{redirect|Ice Bear|the type of bear|Polar bear||Ice Bears (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Ice Bear\n| series             = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = ice bear \n| caption            = \n| first              = \"We Bare Bears\" (Pilot)<br>\"Our Stuff\"<br> (Actual)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer          = \n| voice              = [[Demetri Martin]]<br>(Original)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Ice-Bear/|title=Voice of Ice Bear|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref><br>Max Mitchell <br>(Young)\n| lbl1               = \n| data1              = \n| full_name          = \n| nickname           = Ice\n| alias              = \n| species            = [[Polar bear]]\n| gender             = [[Male]]\n| color              = #FFFFFF\n}}\nIce Bear is a [[polar bear]]. He is the youngest brother and is usually called bro. Ice Bear is often rather stoic and rarely speaks. When he does, he speaks mostly in the third person and says his name first instead of I as shown in \u00a8The Audition\u00a8. It is revealed in \"Yuri and the Bear\" that Ice Bear was raised by a Russian man named Yuri after his mother was killed by poachers. This is how he learned to speak Russian, and because Yuri spoke exclusively in the third person, this is most likely how Ice Bear obtained the habit. He earned accommodation by learning to chop wood, cook salmon, read maps, study calculus, knit, play [[Uno (card game)|Uno]] with standard cards and speak Russian and English, but was cut adrift into the ocean when Yuri had to let him go to save him from the poachers, and the ice floated away from the mainland. He is multilingual, having been shown to speak Korean, French, Japanese (on \"Losing Ice\")and Russian fluently.  Ice Bear also is able to speak to pigeons in the episode \"Our Stuff.\" He is also a skilled chef, dancer, piano player, a novice at robotics, charade player (on \"My Clique\"; it was revealed on \"The Island\" that he learned to speak very late, and originally used his charades skills to communicate), welder, poet (which he writes in French), roller skater and a [[Mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] (cited as [[Brazilian jiu-jitsu]] on \"Chloe\", but his skill set is closer to [[Taekwondo]] and [[judo]] with skills in [[Nunchaku]], [[Shuriken]] and swords). Ice Bear is the most composed of the brothers, always maintaining an \"ice-cool attitude\" in even the most awkward and embarrassing of situations. As seen in \"Losing Ice\" and \"Coffee Cave\", his brothers often take him for granted and are unappreciative of all the cooking and cleaning he does, although they eventually realize the error of their ways. Ice Bear sleeps in the refrigerator with a fire ax which he can use with either hand. Of the three bears, he has the closest relationship with Chloe, almost acting as a quiet big brother to her.\n{{-}}\n\n==Recurring characters==\n===Chloe Park===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Chloe Park\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Chloe\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Charlyne Yi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Chloe/|title=Voice of Chloe|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref>\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name        = \n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = Human\n| gender           = Female\n}}\nChloe Park doesn't have many friends other than the bears and has a hard time relating to her much older peers. In \"My Clique,\" Chloe finally makes some friends with her college classmates, albeit with the help of the Bears. In the same episode, she is revealed to be [[Multilingualism|bilingual]]. Chloe devotes most of her time to studying in the hopes of having a secure future and becomes stressed when it seems like she is on the verge of failing as evidenced in \"The Library\" and \"Professor Lampwick\". Despite fully knowing that the bears mean well, their antics sometimes stress her too. At one point she was nearly driven insane by the Bears when they got sick in the episode \"Bear Flu\" due to them asking for things. Nevertheless, she adores them and will often rely on them for help. She has shown to be involved with their misadventures such as in \"The Demon\" and \"Road Trip\". She also has an interesting connection with Ice Bear due to his quiet persona meshed with her more open personality as seen in \"Chloe and Ice Bear\". Of the three bears, she is most often seen with him.\n\n===Nom Nom===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Nom Nom\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Viral Video\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Patton Oswalt]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Nom-Nom/|title=Voice of Nom Nom|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref>\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name         = \n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = [[Koala]]\n| gender           = Male\n}}\nNom Nom is a misanthropic self-hating [[koala]]. He is a famous internet star, known for his \"cute\" videos and the main antagonist during the two first seasons, starting a slow redemption from the third season onward. While he doesn't talk in any of his videos, Nom Nom often swears angrily towards everyone he comes in contact with, especially the bears. Grizzly imposes him enough to talk to him and admits that he liked his video, but Nom Nom is self-centered and more concerned with materialistic things, and is very selfish and lashes out at anyone who he doesn't like. One example being in \"The Nom Nom Show\" where he was unwilling to share the spotlight with the Bears, despite the positive reception they received. In \"Viral Video,\" Nom Nom says that he does not want any friends because he finds them unimportant and too loud, and proves his point by kicking Grizz out of his limo. His temper is so short, he lashes out at anyone who even slightly annoys him. In \"Anger Management\", it's revealed that Grizz's hugs genuinely calm him to the point of making him optimistic and friendly. He has further shown a more tolerant side. In \"Nom Nom's Entourage,\" he saves a picture of his time with the Bears and in \"Kyle,\" opened his home to another koala who claimed to be his brother. In \"Vacation\", he finally admits that Grizz is the closest thing to a friend he has. In \"Crowbar Jones: Origins\", Nom Nom is shown to be more tolerant of Grizz though he still finds him a nuisance.\n\n===Charlie===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Charlie\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Charlie\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]]<ref name=\"WBBCast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/we-bare-bears-gets-3rd-season-at-cartoon-network-940884|title='We Bare Bears' Gets 3rd Season at Cartoon Network|last=Greenho|first=Caitlin|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 25, 2016}}</ref>\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name         = \n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = [[Bigfoot]]\n| gender           = Male\n}}\nCharlie is a friendly [[bigfoot]] who wanders alone around the San Francisco woods until he meets the Bears in \"Charlie,\" where they agree to let him live in their cave for a little while via a website called CaveShare. While it is unknown how old he is, he is apparently more than a century old as he is shown living as far back as 1913 as seen in \"El Oso\". It is revealed that, due to his life of solitude, he is socially inept and doesn't know how to be a good friend. This results in him unintentionally causing havoc for the Bears whenever he hangs out with them. He is also constantly harassed by humans trying to get pictures of him, which results in him becoming [[Xenophobia|xenophobic]] towards them and developing a fear of cameras. He has on more than one occasion befriended someone other than the Bears. In \"El Oso\", he made friends with the titular character and in \"Rescue Ranger\", he mildly learns to put up with Tabes, but eventually accepts her as his friend in \"Charlie & Tabes\" after getting her name wrong numerous times (Tubes, Tebs, etc.). In \"Hurricane Hal\", his actual home is shown to be a broken-down car while in \"Christmas Parties\" he lives in a giant tree. In the episode \"Charlie Ball,\" we see that Charlie is extremely skilled at ball-handling and that his height makes him perfect for [[basketball]]. In \"Charlie's Big Foot,\" Charlie is revealed to have blue-colored blood and a very jointed body, mostly due to being harmed by the wilderness which he views as perfectly normal, and in \"Bubble\", it is revealed that his natural fur is actually gold colored making him look handsome and majestic. He also sees Panda as his best friend and usually tries to show off new discoveries and his \"decor\" to him over the other two. Besides Panda, he also is friends with a common snake as seen in \"Charlie and the Snake\".\n\n===Ranger Tabes===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Ranger Tabes\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Ranger Tabes\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Cameron Esposito]]<ref name=\"WBBCast\" />\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name         = Dana Tabes\n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = Human\n| gender           = Female\n}}\nRanger Dana Tabes is a [[National Park Service ranger|park ranger]]. She lives in a trailer-style mobile home located in the park where the Bears live. They first meet her in \"Ranger Tabes\" where she helps them locate a missing package. She is shown to be overly confident, persistent and even downright obsessive with wanting to help people. Her obsession is explored in \"Creature Mysteries\" where she tries to capture and prove Charlie's existence. In that same episode, it's revealed that her mother was also a park ranger and the one who inspired her to become one. Her obsession is also prominent in \"Poppy Rangers\" where she was willing to lead a team of girl scouts, called the Poppy Rangers, into a dangerous cave, against Grizzly's wishes. Despite her quirky personality, the Bears consider her as one of their closest friends and praise her to some extent as seen in \"Ranger Norm\". Out of all of them, Tabes seems to coerce with Grizz the most and usually has him around as an assistant to help in leading the Poppy Rangers. Based on how much she relies on him, they seem to have mutual respect for each for other. In \"Ranger Games\", it is revealed that she has a rival in the form of '''Ranger Zhao''' (voiced by [[Ming-Na Wen]]) who leads her own group of girl scouts called the Ivy Rangers. In \"Bear Squad\", Tabes is shown to possess deduction skills to the level of identifying animals and people by a limited amount of evidence. In the same episode, it is revealed that she is banned from doing any ranger work in the city. Over time, Tabes is shown to have calmed down a bit, though she still takes her job very seriously. She has even learned to be more surveillant with her duties and upon knowledge of Charlie's true existence has opted to watch and protect him from afar. By the end of \"Rescue Ranger\", she mildly becomes friends with Charlie and, like the Bears, decides to keep him a secret. Eventually, the two become good friends after he helps her finds her dog Kirk in \"Tabes & Charlie\".\n\n===Lucy===\n{{Infobox character\n| name             = Lucy\n| series           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"Panda's Date\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Daniel Chong (animator)|Daniel Chong]]\n| portrayer        = \n| voice            = [[Ellie Kemper]]<ref name=\"WBBCast\" />\n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| full_name         = \n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| species          = Human\n| gender           = Female\n}}\nLucy is a friend to the Bears and runs a produce delivery service called ''Lucy's Produce''. She first appears in \"Panda's Date\" where she takes an immediate liking to the Bears and their goofy personalities. Panda quickly (as usual) develops a crush on her, but she seems to be unaware of his feelings. She finally returns in season 3 episode, \"Lucy's Brother\" where it is revealed that she delivers fruit to the Bears every Friday. In that same episode, she is shown to have a younger brother named Clifford whom she cares for and worries over immensely. She is also shown to be a terrible dancer, something which Panda was nervous telling her about, but she learns to accept after he realizes how important it is, to be honest, and faithful to her. Despite being oblivious to Panda's feelings for her, the two share a mutual friendship. In \"The Limo\", Lucy begins dating '''Kale''' (voiced by [[Omid Abtahi]]) which upsets Panda, but he ultimately accepts as her happiness is what matters.\n{{-}}\n\n==Minor characters==\n===Pigeon Cartel===\nThe Pigeon Cartel is composed of pigeons who are actually an underground illegal trading ring. They are the closest thing to arch-enemies the Bears have and first appeared in \"Our Stuff\". They stole the Bears' items, which included Grizz's wallet, Panda's cell phone and Ice Bear's ninja stars, along with a wide variety of other expensive and important items around the city. The Bears unintentionally landed in their hideout where the cartel or at least a subgroup of them were arrested. In \"Pigeons\", they are revealed to have a member in their ranks named '''Brenda''' whom Grizz ends up befriending. Brenda actually tricks Grizz into helping her free her gang from prison, or rather the pigeon coup inside the prison, she ultimately has a change of heart due to Grizz's kindness.\n\n===Chloe's Family===\n* '''Mr. Park''' (voiced by Jinkoo Jeong) is Chloe's father. He was initially reserved about Chloe hanging out with the bears, but warms up to their presence in \"Slumber Party\". He is bilingual.\n* '''Mrs. Park''' (voiced by [[Niki Yang]]) is Chloe's mother. She is very supportive of Chloe's friendship with the bears as evidenced when she makes sandwiches for them in \"Chloe and Ice Bear\". She is bilingual.\n* '''Jon Park''' (voiced by Bert Youn) is Chloe's cousin. He appeared in \"Christmas Parties\" where is shown to be rather cocky and doesn't get along with Chloe very well. He has a habit of pranking her every chance he gets and always gets away with it.\n\n===Farmer===\nFarmer (voiced by Kyler Spears) is Nom Nom's personal [[bodyguard]]. He was initially known as '''Bodyguard #1''' due to his primary task of protecting Nom Nom who in turn didn't think much of him. However, this all changed in the episode \"Kyle\" where it is shown that Farmer genuinely cares for Nom Nom's security when he suspected that the titular koala was trying to scam Nom Nom. After rescuing his employer, Nom Nom became more aware of him and asked for his real name, calling him Farmer from that point on.\n\n===Rangers===\n*'''Kirk''' is a dog that Tabes was given as a Christmas present by the Bears in \"Christmas Parties\". In \"Lunch with Tabes,\" he is shown to be rather clever and mischievous. In \"Tabes & Charlie\", he is revealed to have fathered three pups with a wolf.\n* '''Ranger Martinez''' (voiced by [[Keith Ferguson (voice actor)|Keith Ferguson]]) is Tabes' partner. He has been a park ranger since Tabes was a child and was initially her mother's partner. In his old age, he is always prone to sleep and is shown to be rather laid back. He is also very friendly with the Bears.\n* '''Poppy Rangers''' are the team of girl scouts that Ranger Tabes, and to a certain extent Grizz, lead in a variety of tasks and activities. Their ranks include '''Diaz''' (voiced by Marissa Soto), a \"curious and witty\" girl who aspires to be a [[biologist]]; '''Parker''' (voiced by Danity Harris), a \"quiet and confidant\" girl who aspires to be an [[Aerospace engineering|aeronautical engineer]]; '''Murphy''' (voiced by Stella Balick-Karrer), a \"cheerful and patient\" girl who aspires to be a [[geologist]]; '''Nguyen''' (voiced by Audrey Huynh) another \"quiet and confident\" girl who aspires to be a [[principal dancer]] and '''Wallace''' (voiced by Cate Gragnani) an eye-patch wearing \"fearless...born leader\" who aspires to be a park ranger like Tabes. It is unknown whether Wallace has only injured her eye or lost it, only stating that \"it was worth it\". The girls unanimously trust Tabes' leadership and advice, but also adore Grizz whom they affectionately call 'Bear Guy', even though they are well aware of his flaws such as in \"Ranger Games\" and even admit that he is terrible at leading as seen in \"Lord of the Poppies\". In the former episode, their rivals, the '''Ivy Rangers''', as well as Wallace's younger sister '''Chuck Wallace''' are introduced.\n\n===Clifford===\nClifford (voiced by Hudson West) is Lucy's younger brother. He has many allergies and has trouble socializing with others. He constantly wanders off and is very shy. He starts to like Panda once he is considered a friend. He is also very defensive of his sister, seen as he is aware that many boys use him as an attempt to get close to her and gets mad at Panda for doing so. Fortunately, he and Panda reconcile and consider each other close friends.\n\n===Darrell===\nDarrell Saragosa (voiced by [[Mel Rodriguez]]) a 35-year-old man, is a friend to the Bears and owns a [[mousepad]] store called ''Super Rad Mousepads''. He first appears in \"Losing Ice\" where he answers a want ad from Grizz and Panda asking for a replacement for the missing Ice Bear. He happily takes the job, despite the harsh conditions, and later makes them realize their error in taking Ice Bear for granted. He lives with his grandma, Emma, who apparently does most of his cooking. He returns in \"Bear Lift\" where the Bears help his fledgling business. It's also shown that in his youth his store was once booming and brought people together, but over time it began to wear away. By the end, the Bears help bring the store back due to its 'retro' appeal. In \"Best Bears\" Darrell gets married to '''Sofia''' (voiced by Brigitte Kali Canales), a [[hang gliding]] instructor and [[fashion design]]er who thinks that he and the Bears are cool.\n\n===Yana===\nYana (voiced by [[Margarita Levieva]]) is a Russian woman with dark connections to Ice Bear. She is an aggressive woman with a sentimental side to her as well. She and Ice Bear have known each other for a long time and have been on missions together for unknown reasons. Yana first appeared in \"Icy Nights\" where she briefly helped Ice Bear look for his Roomba. She returns in \"Icy Nights II\" where she is kidnapped by Barry, a tech genius who is after the Roomba. At the end of the episode, it's revealed that Yana's father is Yuri, the same man who raised Ice Bear. It's unknown if Yuri is still in contact with her or knows that she's still alive.\n\n===Barry===\nBarry Charles (voiced by [[Kevin McHale (actor)|Kevin McHale]]) is a technical expert and Ice Bear's nemesis. He leads a gang of techies and is involved in illegal activities. His main goal is to steal Ice Bear's Roomba due to the technical specifications it possesses. The reason for doing this is so that he can earn the approval of his father, something that is a sore spot for him.\n\n===Marie===\nMarie (voiced by Edi Patterson) is a web show host that the Bears occasionally watch. She hosts the show ''Mornings with Marie'' off from the website ''[[YouTube|Everyone's Tube]]''. She tends to report on all the latest crazes and current things usually from the internet such as Nom Nom and Panda's sudden popularity like in \"Panda's Sneeze\". Marie also hosts the ''Cute-Off'', a competition where two animals from viral videos participate.\n\n===The Bros===\nThe Bros are the human doppelgangers to the Bears. They first appeared in \"Panda's Friend\". They fittingly display qualities similar to, but also superior to the actual bears.\n* '''Tom''' (voiced by Bert Youn) is Panda's counterpart. He is a small, presumably Asian, man, who wears glasses and typically wears a black hoodie with a white stripe going through it so as to resemble a panda. He, just like Panda, loves Korean dramas and anime and is apparently 97% similar. He becomes way too attached to Panda and kidnaps him from his home and moves him into his apartment. When he realizes how obsessive he has become he leaves (or rather falls) and meets his other two roommates Griff and Isaac. He is much more stable with the two and in \"Bro Brawl\" implies that they are his only real family as well. In that same episode, he states that he has a girlfriend.\n* '''Griff''' (voiced by Eric Edelstein in \"Panda's Friend\" and later by Faruq Tauheed) is Grizz's counterpart. Griff is a \"renegade\" cop, later revealed to be a mall cop, who loves his job and is capable of helping people, as opposed to Grizz who has no job and, while helpful, is socially inept. He is a well built African-American man who usually wears a blue shirt. He seems to care a lot about his roommates and in his first appearance was nervous about losing his home for not meeting the roommate quota until Tom literally dropped in. In \"The Mall\", he is shown to be very friendly with Grizz.\n* '''Isaac''' (voiced by Demetri Martin) is Ice Bear's counterpart. Isaac is a \"five-star chef\" who, much like Ice Bear, is tall and quiet. He wears a white hoodie with the hood always over his head and his blonde bangs hanging out. When he speaks he follows Ice Bear's speech mannerisms by talking in the third person. He sleeps in a walk-in closet, like how Ice Bear sleeps in a fridge and also seems to possess many outlandish abilities. In \"Bro Brawl\" he one up Ice Bear due to not having any hair in his food. In \"The Mall\", he and Ice Bear seem to view each other as rivals.\n\n===Captain Craboo===\nCaptain Craboo is the Bears' pet crab whom they adopted in the episode \"Emergency\". He actually came from the supermarket which Grizz went to buy food and immediately fell in love with the crab. Unfortunately, it pinches onto Ice Bear's ear causing him to become catatonic and deranged. Grizz and Panda eventually get Craboo off of Ice Bear and resort to giving him tiny mitts so that he doesn't pinch Ice Bear again. He returns in \"Captain Craboo\" where it is revealed that he has been gone for quite some time and that Ice Bear still has not forgiven him. However, the two later make up. In that same episode, Craboo attacks Nom Nom, making him a wanted fugitive. By the end of the episode, Craboo solemnly leaves the Bears before they release him into the ocean, especially Ice Bear, who took his departure the hardest.\n\n===The Mailman===\nThe Mailman (voiced by Keith Ferguson) is a friendly [[Postal worker|mailman]] that occasionally visits the Bears. He first appears in \"Nom Nom\" where he delivers a toy helicopter to the Bears. He falls into a pit where Ice Bear was trapped by Nom Nom. He shows that he doesn't mind the situation and also didn't seem to mind being left there. He returns in \"Crowbar Jones\" where he was invited to see the titular movie that Grizz had made. He was easily impressed by it and based on his reactions, simply wishes to have friends. In \"Citizen Tabes,\" he was also impressed with Tabes' packaging to the point that he was willing to listen to her ramble about how she did it. In \"I, Butler\", he was interested in playing basketball with the bears even though he creepily appeared from behind their bushes.\n\n===Mad Scientist===\nMad Scientist (voiced by [[Jason Mantzoukas]]) is an unnamed scientist who is constantly plotting against the government. He first appears in \"Grizz Helps\" where Grizz answers a want ad for someone to aid him in traveling back in time. He was going to use a chicken named Mark as a test subject and Grizz had to rescue him for its owner. The scientist reappeared in \"Summer Love\" with a pelican assistant named Gary and tried to use a body swapping machine on Panda. He revealed that he once had a girlfriend named Amelia who joined the space program, implying one of the reasons he kept conspiring against the government.\n\n===Ralph===\nRalph (voiced by [[John DiMaggio]]) is a [[yeti]] who enjoys playing cruel pranks on humans and animals. He first appears in \"Ralph\" where Charlie befriends him due to being a creature just like him, despite the Bears gaining distrust of Ralph due to his mean nature. He ends up abandoning Charlie when the latter refuses to let a group of humans fall off a bridge as part of a prank, considering him a \"snooze-fest\". He appears again in \"Ice Cave\" where he takes over the Bears' cave and freezes its interior, ruling it like a king. He usually puts Charlie down due to his lanky body and pushes over personality, but Charlie stands up to him and puts Ralph in his place.\n\n===Dr. Clark===\nDr. Clark (voiced by Avery Kidd Waddell) is a medical nurse and Nom Nom's personal doctor. He first appeared in \"Charlie's Big Foot\" where he treated Charlie's foot after it broke. He is shown to have a very unusual [[Doctor\u2013patient relationship|bedside manner]] in that he has a very lethargic and slightly disinterested way of speaking. However, he is shown to take his job seriously and looked aghast at seeing Charlie's blood. He returned in \"Vacation\" where he acted as Nom Nom's personal doctor. His diagnosis was that he was stressed and prescribed that he take a vacation with Grizz acting as his coach. Once again, Dr. Clark delivered all of this in a lethargic disinterested attitude. In \"Braces\", he is revealed to also serve as a dentist and possesses numerous doctoral degrees.\n\n==Guest characters==\n===Paul and Annie===\nPaul (voiced by [[Lou Ferrigno]]) and Annie (voiced by [[Grey DeLisle|Grey Griffin]]) are a married couple that appeared in \"Yard Sale\". Annie is an average looking red-haired woman who was heavily [[Pregnancy|pregnant]]. She sold a box of free things to the Bears at a yard sale she had set up. The things in question were large foam toy fists (which Grizz begins wearing only for them to get stuck to his paws) her husband Paul's phone (which Panda mistakenly takes and begins sending texts unknowingly to Annie) and a pregnancy workout DVD (which Ice Bear begins watching and using to get in better shape). Paul, who resembles a large well-built man, is offended at Panda using his phone and possessively threatens him, but becomes nervous and faints when Annie goes into labor. The Bears band together to get Annie and Paul to the hospital where she successfully gives birth to a baby boy that somehow manages to removes the fake hands off of Grizz, much to everyone's surprise since he had difficulty removing them before.\n\n===Professor Lampwick===\nProfessor Lampwick (voiced by [[Malcolm McDowell]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Professor-Lampwick/|title=Voice of Professor Lampwick|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 22, 2017}}</ref> is Chloe's science professor at the university and he appeared in his self-titled episode. Lampwick is a tall, lean older man with a sinister and stern personality. He has a notorious reputation for being a difficult professor who refuses second chances with his students. Chloe gets so intimidated by him that she fails her course causing her much grief. However, the Bears decide to kidnap him and bring him back to the cave in an effort to force him to give Chloe a second chance. Lampwick proves to be crafty as he turns the Bears against one another, forcing Chloe to step up and demand a second chance, which he grants. When Chloe passes, Lampwick reveals that he untied his own bonds and was just testing her, admitting that she wasn't the first student to \"kidnap [him] over a grade.\" He briefly returns in \"Hurricane Hal\" where he is shown to have an omniscient presence as he was capable of explaining exactly what each of the Bears was doing and apparently is aware of who Charlie is.\n\n===Andy Bangs===\nAndrew \"Andy\" Bangs (voiced by [[Bo Burnham]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Andy-Bangs/|title=Voice of Andy Bangs|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 22, 2017}}</ref> is a child internet star and Nom Nom's main rival who appeared in \"Nom Nom's Entourage\". Andy's name is a pun on the fact that his videos consist mostly of him popping out of places and shouting \"Bang!\" and that he has [[Hair coloring|dyed]] [[Bangs (hair)|bangs]]. He takes great pleasure in humiliating and outsmarting Nom Nom using his trademark surprise gimmick. One thing he has over Nom Nom, is the fact that he is constantly surrounded by his entourage, which Nom Nom lacks forcing him to hire the Bears. Nom eventually manages to get back at Andy by surprising him with his signature \"Bang!\".\n\n===Karla and Dave===\nKarla (voiced by [[Felicia Day]]) and Dave (voiced by [[Jake Johnson]]) are a pair of castaways that the baby Bears encounter in \"The Island\". The Bears are rescued from quicksand by Karla and Dave who have been shipwrecked on the island for some unspecified amount of time. All that is known is that they came separately. Karla mostly misses her sister whom she loves very much and forms a motherly bond with the baby Bears, while Dave displays a slightly disinterested attitude. It eventually becomes clear, that Dave has been misleading Karla and the Bears and that he wants Karla to stay with him alone. The Bears rescue Karla from Dave and escape on an inflatable raft they found, leaving Dave all alone. Karla is rescued by a passing ship, but the Bears float on until they end up in [[Japan]].\n\n===Yuri===\nYuri (voiced by [[Darin De Paul]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/tv-shows/We-Bare-Bears/Yuri/|title=Voice of Yuri|website=Behind the Voice Actors|accessdate=November 22, 2017}}</ref> is an old Russian man who lived out in the arctic as a [[hermit]] [[Survivalism|survivalist]], until he met baby Ice Bear in the episode \"Yuri and the Bear\". A tall, large bearded man who much like Ice Bear, had a tendency to speak in the third person, Yuri lived in a life of solitude after losing his family to some unknown causes. He took Ice Bear under his wing, after some reluctance, and taught him everything that he knew. They were confronted by a hunter, who is implied to have killed Ice Bear's family, and Yuri is forced to cut Ice Bear away from land to save him. In \"Icy Nights II\", it is revealed that Yuri is Yana's father.\n\n===Wyatt===\nWyatt (voiced by [[Ron Funches]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bubbleblabber.com/review-we-bare-bears-road-trip/|title=Review: We Bare Bears \"Road Trip\"|last=Schwarz|first=John|website=Bubble Babbler|date=August 7, 2017|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref> is the overly kind leader of a [[Outlaw motorcycle club|bike gang]] in \"Road Trip\". Wyatt is a random individual that Chloe and the Bears encounter while on their way to see the meteor shower. He displays a slightly lethargic, yet kind and joking attitude that clicks with Grizz, Panda, and Chloe but annoys Ice Bear. He claims that he lost his bike gang and is allowed to ride with them, much to Ice Bear's chagrin. Eventually, Ice Bear manages to take off without him only to have the car run out of gas. Wyatt shows up with his gang and they offer to share their gas with them. Later on, he joins Chloe and the Bears in watching the meteor shower.\n\n===Warren and Faye===\nWarren (voiced by [[Robert Clotworthy]]) and Faye (voiced by [[Frances Conroy]]) are a friendly elderly couple who live in a [[Recreational vehicle|RV]] in the woods somewhere near where the Bears live. They appear in the episode \"Neighbors\" and are depicted as an overly kind couple who immediately take joy in conversing with the Bears. While Panda and Ice Bear find them pleasant, Grizz finds them uncomfortably nice as the two are shown touching and examining the Bears. The two begin taking pictures of the Bears going about their day and it is revealed that they keep numerous knives and other cutting instruments, giving the impression that they plan on cutting up or eating the Bears. However, it is revealed that the two are wood carving fanatics and simply wanted the Bears to model for them for their hobby. They forgive the Bears for their snooping. Warren and Fay are named after [[Warren Beatty]] and [[Faye Dunaway]].\n\n===Esteller===\nEsteller (voiced by [[Estelle (musician)|Estelle]]) is a famous pop song singer who Panda and Tom are huge fans of. She appears in the episode \"The Mall\" where she arrives at the titular location to personally sign autographs for her fans, whom she affectionately refers to as her \"starlings\". Esteller is moved by Panda and Tom's willingness to let their shirts be ruined so that they can get a chance to meet her in person. She thanks them and gives them new signed shirts while politely berating the other fans that tried to ruin their shirts to begin with by telling them, \"Don't be jerks.\" Estelle sings the series' theme song and had previously appeared as herself in the episode \"More Everyone's Tube\" where she sang the full version.\n\n===Charles Barkley===\n[[Charles Barkley]] as himself appears in the episode \"Baby Bears Can't Jump\". He is a famous basketball player that the bears admire when they find a basketball card about him.\n\n===T-Pain===\n[[T-Pain]] as himself appears in the episode \"The Limo\". He is a rapper. It is revealed that he watched Grizz's Crowbar Jones series. Panda is a fan of the rapper.\n\n===Monsta X===\n[[Monsta X]] as themselves appear in the episode \"Panda's Birthday\". The group comprises seven members: Shownu, Wonho, Minhyuk, Kihyun, Hyungwon, Jooheon, and I.M. Panda is a fan of the K-pop group, but Grizz and Ice Bear are not, since they mixed up the group with another metal rock group called Monta S.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cartoon Network}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:We Bare Bears}}\n[[Category: Cartoon Network Studios series and characters]]\n[[Category:Lists of characters in American television animation]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2015|*, We Bare Bears]]\n[[Category: Fictional polar bears]]\n[[Category:Fictional pandas]]\n[[Category:We Bare Bears]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_We_Bare_Bears_characters"}
{"title_page": "Victoria Police", "text_new": "{{out of date|date=March 2020}}\n{{about|the agency in the state of Victoria, Australia|the agency in Canada|Victoria Police Department}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n|agencyname = Victoria Police\n|badge = Badge of Victoria Police.svg\n|badgecaption = Badge of the Victoria Police\n|flag = Flag of the Victoria Police.svg\n|flagcaption = Flag of the Victoria Police\n|imagesize = \n|motto = Uphold the Right <br /><small>''Tenez le Droit\" until November 1986''</small>\n|divtype = State\n|divname = Victoria\n|divdab = Victoria (Australia)\n|country = Australia\n|map             = Victoria in Australia.svg\n|mapcaption      = Victoria Police jurisdiction \n|formedyear = 1853\n|formedmonthday = 8 January\n|chief1name = [[Graham Ashton]]\n|chief1position = Chief Commissioner\n|officetype = Region\n|officename = Western, Eastern, North West Metro, Southern Metro<ref name=\"Victoria Police Boundaries\">{{cite web | url=http://www.police.vic.gov.au/content.asp?Document_ID=7 | title=Victoria Police Boundaries | publisher=Victoria Police | accessdate=30 October 2016}}</ref>\n|governingbody = Government of Victoria\n|electeetype = Minister\n|minister1name = [[Lisa Neville]]\n|minister1pfo = Minister for Police<ref name=\"Minister for police\">{{cite web | url=http://www.vic.gov.au/contactsandservices/directory/?ea0_lfz99_120.&roleWithSubordinates&b348244a-5967-422d-a7cc-b3d82598a328 | title=Victorian Government Directory | publisher=Victorian Government | accessdate=30 October 2016}}</ref>\n|overviewbody = Independent Broad-based Anti-corruption Commission (IBAC) (Formerly [[Office of Police Integrity]])\n|constitution1   = [http://www5.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/vic/consol_act/vpa2013164/ Victoria Police Act 2013]\n|headquarters = Victoria Police Centre <br>637 [[Flinders Street, Melbourne|Flinders Street]],<br>[[Docklands, Victoria|Docklands]], [[Victoria (Australia)|VIC]] 3008 <br />GPO Box 913<br /> {{coord | -37.8189 | 144.9624 | region:AU-VIC_type:landmark |display=inline,title}}\n|stations = 333 (2018){{Update inline|date=April 2020|reason=}}\n|employees = 19,635 (30 June 2018){{Update inline|date=April 2020|reason=}}\n|sworn = 15,700 (June 2018){{Update inline|date=April 2020|reason=}}\n|budget = A$3.011.5 billion (2018\u201319){{Update inline|date=April 2020|reason=}}\n|police = Yes\n|unitname = {{collapsible list | Air Wing | Arson & Explosives Squad | The Botany Branch | Crime Scene Officers | Central Property Management Unit | Criminal Investigation Unit | [[Critical Incident Response Team]] | The Criminal Proceeds Squad | Divisional Intelligence Unit | Detectives | Dog Squad | Drug Task Force | Forensic Services Department | Family Violence Investigation Unit | General Duties | Highway Patrol | Highway Patrol Solo | Homicide Squad | Licensing Services Branch | Media Unit | Mounted Branch | Prosecutions | Operations Response Unit | Organised Motor Vehicle Theft Squad | Physical training unit | Proactive Media Unit | Professional Standards Command | [[Public Order Response Team]] | Regional Response Unit | Regions and Transit Safety Unit | Search and Rescue Squad | Sexual Offences & Child Abuse Investigation Team | Vehicle Impound Unit | [[Victoria Police Special Operations Group|Special Operations Group]] | Psychology Unit | Sex Industry Coordination Unit | State Surveillance Unit | Water Police}}\n|website = [http://police.vic.gov.au/ police.vic.gov.au]\n[http://vicpolicenews.com.au/ vicpolicenews.com.au]\n}}\n\n'''Victoria Police''' is the primary [[law enforcement agency]] of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia. It was formed in 1853 and now operates under the ''Victoria Police Act 2013''<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://content.police.vic.gov.au/sites/default/files/2019-01/VicPolAnnualReport2018.pdf|title=ANNUAL REPORT 2017 - 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://police.vic.gov.au/content.asp?Document_ID=3|title=About Victoria Police|date=16 Oct 2014|website=Victoria Police|publisher=Victoria Police|access-date=30 Aug 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829014114/http://www.police.vic.gov.au/content.asp?Document_ID=3|archive-date=29 August 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/domino/Web_Notes/LDMS/LTObject_Store/ltobjst9.nsf/DDE300B846EED9C7CA257616000A3571/402FEDC7085B3363CA257F9A001D956F/$FILE/13-81aa014%20authorised.pdf|title=Victoria Police Act 2013|last=|first=|date=20 April 2016|website=Legislation Victoria|publisher=Government of Victoria|access-date=30 Aug 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018|June|30|df=}}, Victoria Police had over 19,635 members, including 73 Protective Services Officers and 238 Police Recruits in training, 2 reservists and 3,231 civilian staff across 333 police stations. It had a budget of A$3.011bn with an expenditure of 3.064bn.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nBetween 31 July 2017 and 30 June 2018, Victoria Police responded to 892,374 emergency calls, a reduction of 13.9% from previous year.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:Australian Mounted Police Victoria-edit1.jpg|thumb|left|[[Mounted police|Mounted officers]] of the Victoria Police]]\nThe early settlers of Melbourne provided their own police force and in 1840 there were 12 constables who were paid two [[shillings]] and nine [[pence]] per day and the chief constable was Mr. W (Tulip) Wright.<ref name=Street1954>{{Citation\n | title = Port Phillip \u2013 1840\u20131850 Part II\n | url = http://handle.slv.vic.gov.au/10381/144141\n | year = 1954\n | author = Street, B. A.\n | journal = Victorian Historical Magazine\n | pages = 45\n | volume = 26\n | issue = 102\n | accessdate = 29 August 2013\n}}</ref> Charles Brodie followed Wright as chief constable in 1842 and was succeeded by W. J. Sugden who held the positions of 'town chief constable' and superintendent of the local fire brigade.<ref name=Street1954/> By 1847 there were police in 'country centres' and the Melbourne force was composed of 'one chief officer, four sergeants, and 20 petty constables'.<ref name=Street1954/> There was also 'a force of 28 mounted natives' enlisted and trained by DeVilliers and, later, Captain Pulteney Dana.<ref name=Street1954/>\n\nThe Snodgrass Committee was established in early 1852 to \"identify the policing needs of the colony\" and, following the Committee's report in September 1852, the Victoria Police was formally established on 8 January 1853<ref>Palmer, Darren. A new police in Victoria: conditions of crises or politics of reform? [150 Years of the Victoria Police. Published jointly by the Royal Historical Society of Victoria and the Victoria Police Historical Society.] [online]. Victorian Historical Journal (1987), v.74, no.2, Oct 2003: 167\u2013196. Availability: <http://search.informit.com.au/fullText;dn=200312168;res=APAFT> {{ISSN|1030-7710}}. [cited 29 Aug 13].</ref> from an existing colonial police force of 875 men. Later that month [[William Henry Fancourt Mitchell]] was 'gazetted as Chief Commissioner of Police for the Colony of Victoria'.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38455019 |title=VICTORIA. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 January 1853 |accessdate=29 August 2013 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn 1853, Victoria Police was the first police organisation in Australia who merged all its police entities into one organisation under Victoria Police Chief Commissioner William Mitchell. Victoria continues to be the only state in Australia with a Chief Commissioner of Police.<ref>5426_vpo_policelife_winter15_fa_dig</ref>\n\nTheir first major engagement was the following year, 1854, in support of British soldiers during the events leading up to, and confrontation at, the [[Eureka Stockade]] where some miners (mostly Irish), police and soldiers were killed. From a report at the time: 'the troops and Police were under arms, and just at the first blush of dawn they marched upon the camp at Eureka'.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4801309 |title=FURTHER PARTICULARS OF THE BALLAARAT AFFRAY. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=5 December 1854 |accessdate=29 August 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nMitchell resigned as Chief Commissioner and [[Charles MacMahon (politician)|Charles MacMahon]], was appointed acting chief commissioner that same year.<ref>[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/macmahon-sir-charles-4128 Charles MacMahon], [[Australian Dictionary of Biography]], Volume 5, [[Melbourne University Press|MUP]], 1974.</ref> After the formation of the Victorian Police, the first recorded death on duty was Edward Gray in 1853, followed by William Hogan in 1854, both of drowning.<ref>{{Cite web  |title = Victoria Police 1800\u20131899 Honour Roll | url = http://www.police.vic.gov.au/content.asp?document_id=30489 | publisher = Victoria Police  | date = 20 September 2012 | accessdate = 29 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe following couple of decades saw the growth of the police force, including the beginning of construction of the [[Russell Street, Melbourne|Russell Street]] police station in 1859.<ref>{{Cite web  |title = Victoria Police History | url = http://www.police.vic.gov.au/content.asp?document_id=12325 | publisher = Victoria Police  | date = 2 December 2010 | accessdate = 29 August 2013 }}</ref>\n[[File:Mansfield-police-photomontage.jpg|thumb|upright|Clockwise from top left: Constable Lonigan, Sergeant Kennedy, Constable McIntyre and Constable Scanlon.]]\n\n[[File:Brunswick 1893 police await unemployed.jpg|thumb|right|Mounted police outside the Sarah Sands Hotel in [[Brunswick, Victoria|Brunswick]] awaiting a march by the unemployed in 1893.]]\nSix years later, three more officers (Kennedy, Lonigan and Scanlan) who were hunting the [[Kelly Gang]], were killed by them at Stringybark Creek.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5919040 |title=THE POLICE MURDERS. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=30 October 1878 |accessdate=29 August 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5919925 |title=THE POLICE MURDERS. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=5 November 1878 |accessdate=29 August 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Two years later, in 1880, the police confronted the Kelly Gang at [[Glenrowan, Victoria|Glenrowan]]. A shoot-out ensued on 28 June, during which three members of the Kelly Gang were killed and following which [[Ned Kelly]] was shot and captured.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article34470301 |title=LATEST NEWS. |newspaper=[[The Camperdown Chronicle]] |date=29 June 1880 |accessdate=30 August 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn 1888 senior constable John Barry produced the first Victoria Police Guide, a manual for officers.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article88553266 |title=THE VICTORIAN POLICE GUIDE. |newspaper=[[Bendigo Advertiser]] |location=Vic. |date=20 August 1888 |accessdate=30 August 2013 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> (The Victoria Police Manual, as it is now known, remains the comprehensive guide to procedure in the Victoria Police.) Police officers were granted the right to vote in parliamentary elections the same year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article73770255 |title=Police Franchise. |newspaper=The Independent |location=Footscray, Vic. |date=17 November 1888 |accessdate=30 August 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn 1899 the force introduced the Victoria Police Valour Award to recognise the bravery of members.<ref>{{Cite web | title = The Victoria Police Valour Award | url = http://www.vicpolhistory.org.au/VAHistory.aspx | publisher = Victoria Police historical Society | accessdate = 29 August 2013 }}</ref> Three years later, in 1902, the right to a police pension was revoked.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article87831938 |title=VICTORIA. |newspaper=[[The Chronicle (Adelaide)|The Chronicle]] |location=Adelaide |date=15 November 1902 |accessdate=30 August 2013 |page=16 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1917, Victoria Police appointed [[Madge Connor]] as a 'police agent'\u2014while not a full sworn officer, Connor was the first women to be made a member of a police service in Victoria,<ref name=\"aww\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article51189871 |title=The WOMEN Who CHASE CRIMINALS |newspaper=[[The Australian Women's Weekly]] |volume=I |issue=36 |location=Australia, Australia |date=10 February 1934 |accessdate=31 August 2018 |page=15 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and was one of four women to be sworn in as officers in 1924, after she led a successful campaign for equal pay and status within the force.<ref name=\"adb-connor\">{{cite AuDB |first=Colleen |last=Woolley |author-link= |title= 'Connor, Madge Irene (1874\u20131952)' |volume= |edition= |year= |id2=connor-madge-irene-12854 |access-date=31 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===1923 Victoria Police strike===\n{{main|1923 Victorian Police strike}}\n\nOn 31 October 1923 members of the Victoria Police Force refused duty and went on strike over the introduction of a new supervisory system.\nThe police strike led to riots and looting in [[Melbourne]]'s central business district. The Victorian government enlisted special constables, and the [[Commonwealth of Australia]] called out the [[Australian Defence Force|Australian military]]. Victoria Police are the only Australian Police Service to ever go on strike.\n\nOnly a few of the strikers were ever employed as policemen again, but the government increased pay and conditions for police as a result. Members of the Victoria Police (as its officers are generally known) now have among the highest union membership rates of any occupation, at well over 90%. The Victorian police union, the [[Police Association Victoria|Police Association]], remains a very powerful industrial and political force in Victoria.\n\n===Recent history \u2013 controversy and corruption allegations===\nIn the 1980s and 1990s allegations were made against most [[:Category:Law enforcement agencies of Australia|Australian police forces]] of corruption and graft, culminating in the establishment of several [[Royal Commission]]s and anti-corruption watchdogs. Inquiries have also been held into Victoria Police (Beach ''et al.''). The force was criticised because members of the public (both innocent and guilty) were being fatally shot at a rate exceeding that of all other [[:Category:Law enforcement agencies of Australia|Australian police forces]] combined.<ref name=\"theage.com.au\">{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/vicelection06news/new-lethal-weapons-for-police/2006/11/14/1163266550686.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1 | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=New lethal weapons for police | date=15 November 2006 | first1=Mathew | last1=Murphy | first2=Andrea | last2=Petrie | first3=Ian | last3=Munro | first4=Farrah | last4=Tomazin}}</ref> Related criticisms emerged after the 2008 [[Death of Tyler Cassidy|killing of Tyler Cassidy]] by Victoria Police officers, which was partly blamed on inadequate training. In later years, numerous edits were made to the Wikipedia article about the killing from police computers, in an attempt to give a more favourable impression of the officers' conduct and the subsequent investigation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Victoria Police edits Wikipedia page of police shooting victim Tyler Cassidy|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/victoria-police-edits-wikipedia-page-of-police-shooting-victim-tyler-cassidy-20150526-gh9vt1?stb=red|date=1 June 2015|work=[[The Age]]|location=Melbourne|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|access-date=6 August 2015|last=Mannix|first=Liam}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, [[Christine Nixon]] was appointed Chief Commissioner, becoming the first woman to head a police force in Australia.\n\nIn May 2004 former police officer [[Simon Illingworth]] appeared on ABC-TV's ''[[Australian Story]]'' documentary program to tell his disturbing story of entrenched [[police corruption]] in Victoria Police. He has also written a book about his experiences entitled ''Filthy Rat''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Illingworth|first=Simon|title=Filthy Rat : One Man's Stand Against Police Corruption and Melbourne's Gangland War |url=http://www.fontainepress.com/filthyrat/|year=2006|publisher=Fontaine Press|location=Fremantle, W.A.|isbn=978-0-9804170-4-3|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2007, Don Stewart, a retired [[Supreme Court of Victoria|Supreme Court]] judge, called for a royal commission into Victorian [[police corruption]]. Stewart alleged that the force was riddled with corruption that the Office of Police Integrity was unable to deal with.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/National/Former-judge-says-Vic-police-are-corrupt/2007/01/11/1168105079090.html | title=Former judge says Vic police are corrupt | date=11 January 2007 | work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn early February 2009, in response to evidence that many of the [[2009 Victorian bushfires]] were deliberately lit, chief commissioner Christine Nixon announced the creation of Taskforce Phoenix to investigate all related deaths during the fires, to be led by assistant commissioner Dannye Moloney of the crime department and was composed of around 100 police officers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2008/s2487831.htm |title=PM \u2013 Arson taskforce searching for suspects |publisher=ABC Online |date= |accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2009, [[Simon Overland]] was named as the new chief commissioner, replacing [[Christine Nixon]], who was retiring.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/story/0,27574,25125866-1243,00.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306121345/http://www.news.com.au/story/0,27574,25125866-1243,00.html|date=6 March 2009}}</ref> On June 2011 Overland announced his decision to resign prematurely with effect from 1 July 2011 over what many assume were the allegations of corruption, the [[Ombudsman Victoria|ombudsman]] criticism and the government pressure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-06-16/overland-denies-he-quit-over-crime-stats/2760482|title=Overland denies he quit over crime stats|date=2011-06-16|language=en-AU|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/oldschool-policeman-takes-on-daunting-job-20110616-1g63h.html|title=Old-school policeman takes on 'daunting' job|last=Millar|first=Paul|website=The Age|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/corruption-warning-over-handling-of-crime-stats-20110503-1e6wv.html|title=Corruption warning over handling of crime stats|last=McKenzie|first=Richard Baker and Nick|website=The Age|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011 then acting chief commissioner [[Ken Lay (police officer)|Ken Lay]] was named as chief commissioner after five months' caretaking.\n\nOn 21 October 2011 the police force evicted [[Occupy Melbourne]] protesters from [[Melbourne City Square]]. Despite 173 arrests being made, no charges have been laid against any protesters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/protesters-arrested-as-chaos-descends-on-cbd-20111021-1mb07.html | title=Protesters arrested as chaos descends on CBD | publisher=The Age | date=22 October 2011 | work=The Age }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December 2014 Lay announced he was stepping down as the chief commissioner of Victoria Police after three years of service, taking leave until his resignation took effect on 31 January 2015. Deputy chief commissioner Tim Cartwright was acting in the role until a new commissioner was appointed.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/victoria-police-chief-commissioner-ken-lay-steps-down-20141229-12ewu7.html|title = Victoria Police Chief Commissioner Ken Lay steps down|date = 29 December 2014|accessdate = 2014-12-30|website = The Age|publisher = Rania Spooner, Tammy Mills|last = |first = }}</ref> On 25 May 2015, Deputy Commissioner [[Graham Ashton]] of the Australian Federal Police was announced as the new chief commissioner\u2014he took up the role in July 2015.<ref name=ashtoncomm>{{cite news|title=Graham Ashton appointed Chief Commissioner of Victoria Police|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-05-25/graham-ashton-appointed-victoria-police-chief-commissioner/6494984|accessdate=25 May 2015|work=ABC News|date=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, the treasurer announced an investment of $586&nbsp;million into Victoria Police. From those, $540&nbsp;million will be used to employ 406 additional sworn police officers and 52 additional specialist staff, technology upgrades and an expanded forensic capability of Victoria Police; $36.8&nbsp;million to replace and refurbish a number of police stations in regional and rural areas; $19.4&nbsp;million to continue the Community Crime Prevention Program; $63&nbsp;million to enhance counter-terrorism capability, including an additional 40 sworn police officers and 48 additional specialist staff to investigate and respond to an increased terror threat. The budget also funds a package of initiatives for all Victoria Police employees to help deal with mental health problems.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.budget.vic.gov.au/program_project/police |title=Police |author=Andreou, Helen |date=2016-04-22 |website=www.budget.vic.gov.au |language=en|access-date=2016-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Victoria Police employed The Victorian Equal Opportunity and Human Rights Commission (VEOHRC) to examine the nature and prevalence of sex discrimination, including predatory behaviour, amongst Victoria Police personnel.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.victorianhumanrightscommission.com/VPIR/index.php/about-the-review|title=About the review|website=www.victorianhumanrightscommission.com|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref> [[Kate Jenkins]] was appointed the Commissioner<ref name=\":5\" /> and, in mid December 2015, VEOHRC revealed its findings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.humanrightscommission.vic.gov.au/our-resources-and-publications/reports/item/download/8430_75bc5f7c5246c507c7ee7bffca78730e|title=Human Rights Commission|last=|first=|date=Dec 2015|website=Human Rights Commission|publisher=Human Rights Commission|access-date=30 Aug 2016}}</ref> Shortly after, on 9 December 2015, Victoria Police Chief Commissioner Ashton apologised over the high tolerance and prevalence of sexual harassment and the sexual discrimination and gender inequality within Victoria Police. Ashton pledged a change of direction and the implementation of all 20 recommendations by VEOHRC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-09/high-rate-of-sexual-harrassment-in-victoria-police-report-says/7012288|title=Victoria Police chief apologises over damning sexual harassment findings|date=2015-12-08|language=en-AU|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, [[Transport Accident Commission]] (TAC) notified Victoria Police of \"anomalies\" in the preliminary breath tests statistics data. TAC and Victoria Police analyzed more than 17.1m tests starting February 2012 and found that 258,463, or less than 1.5% tests were probably false.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/breaking-news/vic-police-faked-258000-breath-tests/news-story/b643640da6dea0a38ca8518a53d329a9|title=Fake breath tests cost Vic Police funding|work=NewsComAu|access-date=2018-06-08}}</ref> As a result, in mid 2018, TAC froze $4m funding to Victoria Police operations. Victoria Police also started an internal investigation into the matter, notified [[Independent Broad-based Anti-corruption Commission|IBAC]] and appointed former chief commissioner [[Neil Comrie]] to conduct an investigation into the causes.<ref name=\":11\"/><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-30/victoria-police-record-fake-roadside-breath-tests/9817846|title=Victoria Police lose $4m in funding over faked roadside breath tests|date=2018-05-30|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-06-08|language=en-AU}}</ref> A preliminary report suggested that unrealistic management demands of between 50 and 100 [[breath test]]s per shift was a possible cause to faking the tests. The methods used by police officers was that of placing a finger over the straw entry hole of breath testing equipment or blowing into the straw themselves.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nIn April 2018, Victoria Police officers from the Preston station were suspended 'over allegations of brutality' and a fifth, from the Bendigo area, has 'been assigned to other duties' following a claim 'in which a man had his head thrown against a police cell door'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/four-police-officers-involved-in-brutality-claims-suspended-20180406-p4z875.html|title=Four police officers involved in brutality claims suspended|work=The Age|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Uniform history ===\nBetween 1853 and 1877, when the first Victoria Police officers emerged, the uniforms resembled the military style of the day. Mounted and foot officers wore dark blue jackets buttoned to the neck. Mounted troops wore [[sword]]s whilst the Gold Escorts carried [[revolver]]s and [[rifle]]s. The foot patrols, as equipment, had wooden batons, notebooks, [[handcuffs]] and a [[whistle]] to call for assistance when in need. The whistles were fixed to the officer tunic by chain which prevented losing the whistle or falling during a foot chase,<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/law-order/from-military-style-to-nypd-navy-blue-the-evolution-of-the-victoria-police-uniform/story-fni0ffnk-1226641832653?nk=bfe316f2fcc9338602f7823784fe32e0-1472601590|title=From military-style to navy blue threads: the evolution of the Victoria Police uniform|access-date=2016-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vicpolhistory.org/images/historical_soc/Journals/2009%20Volume%2011%20Number%202.pdf|title=Magazine of Victoria Police Uniform History|last=|first=|date=2 Nov 2009|website=Victoria Police History|publisher=Victoria Police Historical Society Inc.|access-date=1 Sep 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1877 and until 1947 Victoria Police's uniform resembled [[Police uniforms and equipment in the United Kingdom|British Metropolitan Police]]'s uniform. In 1920, the Wolseley leather \"[[Custodian helmet|bobby]]\" helmet was also introduced. Policeman were wearing striped pieces of cloth (brassards) on their lower left cuffs to show they were on duty. During World War II, Victoria Police issued anti-shrapnel steel helmets, also referred as \"tin hats\".<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nBetween 1947 and 1979, a major uniform change took place for Victorian Police officers. The bobby helmet was replaced by a black cloth peak cap, a silver police badge was introduced along with white shirts and ties for the general police officers. In 1963, a white [[pith helmet]] with a puggaree hatband and a hand-held radio were added to the Victoria Police general duties officers. Along with a new uniform, Victoria Police also introduced the first uniform for women. The uniform for females featured a knee-length skirt, a button-up jacket, a shirt and tie, [[tights]], and peak hats made to fit a lady's hairstyle. Starting with 1972 until 1986, female police officers also carried handbags custom-made to hold batons and firearms.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/dark-blue-hue-a-police-winner-20121205-2auj9.html|title=Dark blue hue a police winner|last=Bucci|first=Nino|website=The Age|access-date=2016-08-31}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1979 and 2013, police uniforms underwent a number of small changes and there were a total of 83 combinations that a police officer could wear. The changes were mainly as need based for the general duties policing with the addition of [[Pepper spray|capsicum sprays]], [[handgun]], [[Baton (law enforcement)|baton]], etc. In 1981, female police officers were approved trousers as part of their uniform and they were issued 54 pantyhose a year. In 2001, the [[baseball cap]] was introduced along with [[akubra]] and a woollen jumper. One major change happened in 2008 with the introduction of the [[Bulletproof vest|Integrated Operational Equipment Vest]].<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn November 1986, Victoria Police announced the transition of the motto from \"Tenez le droit\" to \"Uphold the right\". This change would start taking place in December 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1300&dat=19861107&id=lDUzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3pMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4855,4373280|title=The Age \u2013 Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2016-08-31}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, the new dark navy uniform was introduced to all officers as the new standard. The pants are made from rip-stop fabric, the undergarment made from cotton stretch which can be short sleeved or long sleeved and is to be worn under the ballistic vest. Baseball caps remained, although they are darker in colour than pre 2013. The new dark uniform was designed to look more professional and to hide blood, dirt and sweat. The dark blue uniform was modelled after the Oxfordshire and Northumberland police attires.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Chief Commissioners ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=1 cellpadding=5 cellspacing=0\n! Name || Post-nominals || Term began || Term ended\n|-\n| [[William Henry Fancourt Mitchell|Sir William Mitchell]] || ||align=right| {{dts|1852}} ||align=right| {{dts|1854}} \n|-\n| [[Charles MacMahon (politician)|Sir Charles MacMahon]] || ||align=right| {{dts|1854}} ||align=right| {{dts|1858}} \n|-\n| [[Frederick Standish]] || ||align=right| {{dts|1858}} ||align=right| {{dts|1880}} \n|-\n| [[Hussey Malone Chomley|Hussey Chomley]] || ||align=right| {{dts|1881}} ||align=right| {{dts|1902}}\n|-\n| [[Thomas O'Callaghan]] || ||align=right| {{dts|1902}} ||align=right| {{dts|1913}}\n|-\n| [[George Sainbury|Alfred Sainsbury]] || ||align=right| {{dts|1913}} ||align=right| {{dts|1919}}\n|-\n| [[George Charles Thomas Steward|Sir George Steward]] ||[[Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], [[Volunteer Officers' Decoration|VD]], [[Justice of the peace|JP]]\n| align=\"right\" |{{dts|1919}} ||align=right| {{dts|1920}}\n|-\n| [[John Gellibrand|Sir John Gellibrand]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|KCB|DSO1}} ||align=right| {{dts|1920}} ||align=right| {{dts|1922}}\n|-\n| [[Alexander Nicholson (police officer)|Alexander Nicholson]] || ||align=right| {{dts|1922}} ||align=right| {{dts|1925}}\n|-\n| [[Thomas Blamey|Sir Thomas Blamey]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|CB|CMG|DSO|ED}} ||align=right| {{dts|1925}} ||align=right| {{dts|1936}}\n|-\n| [[Alexander Duncan (police officer)|Alexander Duncan]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|CMG}} ||align=right| {{dts|1937}} ||align=right| {{dts|1954}}\n|-\n| [[Selwyn Porter]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|CBE|DSO}} ||align=right| {{dts|1955}} ||align=right| {{dts|1963}}\n|-\n| [[Rupert Henry Arnold|Rupert Arnold]] || ||align=right| {{dts|1963}} ||align=right| {{dts|1969}}\n|-\n| [[Noel Wilby]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|LVO|QPMd}} ||align=right| {{dts|1969}} ||align=right| {{dts|1971}}\n|-\n| [[Reginald Jackson (police officer)|Reginald Jackson]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|CMG|MVO|QPMd}} ||align=right| {{dts|1971}} ||align=right| {{dts|1977}}\n|-\n| [[Mick Miller (police officer)|Mick Miller]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|AO|LVO|QPMd}} ||align=right| {{dts|1977}} ||align=right| {{dts|1987}}\n|-\n| [[Kel Glare]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|AO|APM}} ||align=right| {{dts|1987}} ||align=right| {{dts|1992}}\n|-\n| [[Neil Comrie]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|AO|APM}} ||align=right| {{dts|1993}} ||align=right| {{dts|2001}}\n|-\n| [[Christine Nixon]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|APM}} ||align=right| {{dts|2001}} ||align=right| {{dts|2009}}\n|-\n| [[Simon Overland]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|APM}} ||align=right| {{dts|2009}} ||align=right| {{dts|2011}}\n|-\n| [[Ken Lay (police officer)|Ken Lay]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|AO|APM}} ||align=right| {{dts|2011}} ||align=right| {{dts|2015}}\n|-\n| [[Graham Ashton]] || {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|AM|APM}} ||align=right| {{dts|2015}} ||align=Centre| ''Incumbent''\n|}\n\n==Rank structure==\n{{see also|Australian police ranks}}\n\nAlthough Victoria Police has a rank structure similar to an army, the organisation insists it is not a paramilitary organisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.police.vic.gov.au/retrievemedia.asp?Media_ID=102508|title=A VISION FOR VICTORIA POLICE IN 2025|last=|first=|date=May 2014|website=Victoria Police|publisher=Victoria Police|access-date=30 Aug 2016}}</ref> However, within Victoria Police, units such as [[Victoria Police Special Operations Group|Special Operations Group]], have been identified as paramilitary units by Victoria Police and by Australian Defence Force.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aic.gov.au/media_library/conferences/2005-policewomen/mcculloch.pdf|title=Community policing, paramilitary policing and implications for women|last=|first=|date=|website=Australian Institute of Criminology|publisher=Australian Institute of Criminology|access-date=30 Aug 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.onlineopinion.com.au/view.asp?article=1266|title=Australia's police and military must not become the same thing \u2013 On Line Opinion \u2013 15/5/2001|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jude|first=McCulloch|date=2001-01-01|title=Blue army : paramilitary policing in Australia|url=http://dro.deakin.edu.au/view/DU:30000376}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jude|first=McCulloch|date=1998-01-01|title=Blue army: paramilitary policing in Victoria|url=https://minerva-access.unimelb.edu.au/handle/11343/39531}}</ref>\n\nAll sworn members start at the lowest rank of constable<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.policecareer.vic.gov.au/police/about-the-role/becoming-a-police-officer|title=Becoming a Police Officer {{!}} About the Role {{!}} Police Members {{!}} Victoria Police|website=www.policecareer.vic.gov.au|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref> and work their way up. After their 2-year probationary period, the Constable gets its confirmation and becomes a permanent addition to Victoria Police.  The newly confirmed Constable can get the insignia of 'First Constable' to distinguish himself between confirmed and non confirmed Constables.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tpav.org.au/Publications_and_Media/InBrief/2011_InBriefs/November_2011/29_November.html|title=The Police Association Victoria \u2013 First Constable (63/11)|website=tpav.org.au|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n\nConstables are promoted ''in situ'' to senior constable after two years of becoming a confirmed Constable and successful completion of re-introduced Senior Constable exams. Promotion beyond senior constable is highly competitive. The newly-promoted officer is in probation for 1 year.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nAll sworn members of Victoria Police have a rank. There are a total of 12 different legislated ranks<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/vic/consol_act/vpa2013164/s13.html|title=VICTORIA POLICE ACT 2013 - SECT 13 Rank structure|website=classic.austlii.edu.au|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref> within Victoria Police. The Chief Superintendent rank is being phased out with no one occupying the rank, making Victoria Police having 11 effective ranks. The last Chief Superintendent was in 2008.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Victoria Police Annual Report 2007 - 2008|last=|first=|publisher=Victoria Police|year=2008|isbn=|location=Victoria, Australia|pages=64}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Constable and non-commissioned ranks<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.police.vic.gov.au/content.asp?document_id=12383|title=Victoria Police \u2013 The rank and file|last=|first=|date=2 Dec 2010|website=Victoria Police|publisher=Victoria Police|access-date=30 Aug 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Rank'''||[[Constable]]||First<br /> constable\n|Senior<br /> Constable||Leading<br /> senior<br /> constable\n|[[Sergeant]]||Senior<br />sergeant\n|-\n|'''Insignia'''||[[File:vic-police-constable.png|50px]]||[[File:Vic-police-first-constable.png|50px|Rank epaulette of a first constable of the Victoria Police.]]||[[File:vic-police-senior-constable.png|50px]]||[[File:vic-police-leading-senior-constable.png|50px]]||[[File:vic-police-sergeant.png|50px]]||[[File:vic-police-senior-sergeant.png|50px]]\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Commissioned ranks<ref name=\":4\" />\n|-\n|'''Rank'''||[[Inspector]]||[[Superintendent (police)|Superintendent]]||Commander||Assistant<br /> commissioner||Deputy<br /> commissioner||Chief<br /> commissioner\n|-\n|'''Insignia'''||[[File:vic-police-inspector.png|50px]]||[[File:vic-police-superintendent.png|50px]]||[[File:vic-police-commander.png|50px]]||[[File:Wa-police-assistant-commissioner.png|50px]]||[[File:vic-police-deputy-commissioner.png|50px]]||[[File:Wa-police-commissioner.png|50px]]\n|}\n\n===Non-commissioned ranks===\nPromotion to the rank of sergeant is merit-based after successful completion of the Sergeant Level Pre-promotional Qualifying Exam. A sergeant normally manages a team during a shift, like Patrol Supervisor of a Police Service Area (PSA) for a shift. A detective sergeant is typically in charge of a team in a specific part of either local detectives at police stations or crime squads.\n\nA senior sergeant oversees the sergeants and traditionally performs more administrative work and middle management duties, for example coordination of policing operations, or specialist work other than active patrol duties. General-duties senior sergeants are traditionally in charge of most police stations or can be a sub-charge (or second in charge) of larger (usually 24-hour) police stations. In each division, or group of divisions on a night shift, a senior sergeant is the division supervisor for a shift and is responsible for managing and overseeing incidents in their area. Detective senior sergeants are usually the officer in charge of crime investigation units.\n\n===Designations===\nAdditional classifications are available for members skilful enough, and upon completion of certain training and work-based performances, for classification of detective at senior constable level. Detectives also hold classification up to superintendent.\n\n===Dissolved ranks===\n{| style=\"text-align:center\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|'''Rank'''||Chief<br /> Inspector||Chief<br /> superintendent\n|-\n|'''Insignia'''||[[File:vic-police-chief-inspector.png|50px]]||[[File:vic-police-chief-superintendent.png|50px]]\n|}\n\nThe ranks of chief inspector and chief superintendent are no longer promotable ranks since the changes in hierarchy in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=The rank and file|url=http://www.police.vic.gov.au/content.asp?document_id=12383|website=Victoria Police|publisher=State Government Victoria|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe previous and last chief superintendent, Peter McDonald, retired from Victoria Police on 30 September 2014.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://www.cwaustral.com.au/emag-1412/11184-3728-19809958/index.html|title = Victoria Police Association Journal|last = |first = |date = December 2014|journal = |doi = |pmid = |access-date = }}</ref> The last Chief Inspector Christopher K. Coster retired on 6 June 2019 after 45 years service. He was the only Chief Inspector to wear the current style and colour uniform.\n\n===Positions===\nLeading senior constable (LSC) used to be listed in the rank structure but was not a rank per se. It was only open for senior constables to apply for and was not a permanent position. If a member transferred to another duty type or station, the officer was then relieved of the position of LSC. It was primarily a position for field training officers who oversees the training and development of inexperienced probationary constables or constables.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n\nThe most recent round of wage negotiations however saw the title of leading senior constable become an actual rank. It is awarded \"in situ\" but only after assessments have been made against the senior constable's ability to move to the higher position. Leading senior constables are now capable of being upgraded to acting sergeant and it is expected that the position is one that people will move through as they are promoted.\n\nMembers who held the position or classification of leading senior constable under the last enterprise bargaining agreements will retain their title and position.\n\n=== Salaries and benefits ===\nOn 15 February 2016, Victoria Police members voted for the 2016 \u2013 2019 [[Enterprise bargaining agreement|Enterprise Bargain Agreement]]. On 4 March 2016, the outcome of the vote was announced but the new EB took effect starting on 1 December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tpav.org.au/Publications_and_Media/InBrief/2016_InBriefs/February_2016/1_February.html|title=The Police Association Victoria \u2013 EBA ballot timelines announced|website=tpav.org.au|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/victoria-police-set-to-get-more-pay-in-new-eba-deal/news-story/2ccdc718e4c2ed7cb539797ec1a08a35?from=herald%2520sun_rss&nk=bfe316f2fcc9338602f7823784fe32e0-1472525323|title=Victoria Police set for a pay boost|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref> Under the new EB, Victoria Police officers will receive increased penalty rates for weekend work, added unsociable and intrusive to weekend work, increased pay for prosecutors and a number of other benefits and entitlements.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fwc.gov.au/documents/documents/agreements/fwa/ae418283.pdf|title=Fair Work Commission|last=|first=|date=21 Mar 2016|website=Fair Work|publisher=Fair Work|access-date=30 Aug 2016}}</ref> The new EB did not include the ranks of Commanders and above.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 2016 \u2013 2019 EB, Victoria Police officers were offered 2.5% increase per year for 4 years starting on 1 December 2015. At first, the new proposed agreement was strongly opposed by [[Police Association of Victoria|The Police Association]] as, in reality, represented only 0.3% increase after inflation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tpav.org.au/Publications_and_Media/InBrief/2015_InBriefs/August_2015/12_August.html|title=The Police Association Victoria \u2013 Why 2.5 Percent is an Insult!|website=tpav.org.au|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-10/victoria-police-pay-dispute-resolved-with-four-year-deal/7017130|title=Victoria Police pay dispute resolved with four-year deal|date=2015-12-10|language=en-AU|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref> However, in December 2015, The Police Association changed their position and supported the new EB.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tpav.org.au/Publications_and_Media/InBrief/2015_InBriefs/December_2015/11_December_2015.html|title=The Police Association Victoria \u2013 What the new EB deal means for your Penalty Rates|website=tpav.org.au|access-date=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Victoria Police salaries<ref name=\":1\" />\n!Rank\n!Increment\n!