{"title_page": "Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology", "text_new": "{{Infobox journal\n| title = Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology\n| cover =\n| editor = Thomas Schimmel\n| discipline = [[Nanotechnology]]\n| former_names =\n| abbreviation = Beilstein J. Nanotechnol.\n| publisher = [[Beilstein Institute for the Advancement of Chemical Sciences]]\n| country = Germany\n| frequency = Continuous\n| history = 2010\u2013present\n| openaccess = Yes\n| license = [[Creative Commons Attribution No Derivatives]]\n| website = http://www.beilstein-journals.org/bjnano\n| link2 = https://www.beilstein-journals.org/bjnano/volumes\n| link2-name = Online archive\n| JSTOR =\n| OCLC = 967839311\n| LCCN = \n| CODEN = BJNEAH\n| ISSN =\n| eISSN = 2190-4286\n}}\nThe '''''Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology''''' is a [[peer-reviewed]] [[platinum open-access]] [[scientific journal]] covering all aspects of [[nanoscience]] and [[nanotechnology]]. It is published by the [[Beilstein Institute for the Advancement of Chemical Sciences]] and the [[editor-in-chief]] is Thomas Schimmel ([[Karlsruhe Institute of Technology]]). The journal was established in 2010.\n\n==Abstracting and indexing==\nThe journal is abstracted and indexed in:\n*[[Chemical Abstracts Service]]<ref name=CASSI>{{cite web |url=http://cassi.cas.org/search.jsp |title=CAS Source Index |publisher=[[American Chemical Society]] |work=[[Chemical Abstracts Service]] |accessdate=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n*[[Current Contents]]/Physical, Chemical & Earth Sciences<ref name=ISI>{{cite web |url=http://mjl.clarivate.com/ |title=Master Journal List |publisher=[[Clarivate Analytics]] |work=Intellectual Property & Science |accessdate=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n*[[Ei Compendex]]<ref name=Compendex>{{cite web |url=http://www.elsevier.com/online-tools/engineering-village/contentdatabase-overview |title=Content/Database Overview - Compendex Source List |publisher=[[Elsevier]] |work=Engineering Village |accessdate=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n*[[Science Citation Index Expanded]]<ref name=ISI/>\n*[[Scopus]]<ref name=Scopus>{{cite web |url=https://www.scopus.com/sourceid/19700190315 |title=Source details: Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology |publisher=[[Elsevier]] |work=Scopus preview |accessdate=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.beilstein-journals.org/bjnano}}\n\n[[Category:Nanotechnology journals]]\n[[Category:Continuous journals]]\n[[Category:English-language journals]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 2010]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox journal\n| title = Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology\n| cover =\n| editor = Thomas Schimmel\n| discipline = [[Nanotechnology]]\n| former_names =\n| abbreviation = Beilstein J. Nanotechnol.\n| publisher = [[Beilstein Institute for the Advancement of Chemical Sciences]]\n| country = Germany\n| frequency = Continuous\n| history = 2010\u2013present\n| openaccess = Yes\n| license = [[Creative Commons Attribution No Derivatives]]\n| impact = 2.968\n| impact-year = 2017\n| website = http://www.beilstein-journals.org/bjnano\n| link2 = https://www.beilstein-journals.org/bjnano/volumes\n| link2-name = Online archive\n| JSTOR =\n| OCLC = 967839311\n| LCCN = \n| CODEN = BJNEAH\n| ISSN =\n| eISSN = 2190-4286\n}}\nThe '''''Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology''''' is a [[peer-reviewed]] [[platinum open-access]] [[scientific journal]] covering all aspects of [[nanoscience]] and [[nanotechnology]]. It is published by the [[Beilstein Institute for the Advancement of Chemical Sciences]] and the [[editor-in-chief]] is Thomas Schimmel ([[Karlsruhe Institute of Technology]]). The journal was established in 2010.\n\n==Abstracting and indexing==\nThe journal is abstracted and indexed in:\n*[[Chemical Abstracts Service]]<ref name=CASSI>{{cite web |url=http://cassi.cas.org/search.jsp |title=CAS Source Index |publisher=[[American Chemical Society]] |work=[[Chemical Abstracts Service]] |accessdate=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n*[[Current Contents]]/Physical, Chemical & Earth Sciences<ref name=ISI>{{cite web |url=http://mjl.clarivate.com/ |title=Master Journal List |publisher=[[Clarivate Analytics]] |work=Intellectual Property & Science |accessdate=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n*[[Ei Compendex]]<ref name=Compendex>{{cite web |url=http://www.elsevier.com/online-tools/engineering-village/contentdatabase-overview |title=Content/Database Overview - Compendex Source List |publisher=[[Elsevier]] |work=Engineering Village |accessdate=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n*[[Science Citation Index Expanded]]<ref name=ISI/>\n*[[Scopus]]<ref name=Scopus>{{cite web |url=https://www.scopus.com/sourceid/19700190315 |title=Source details: Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology |publisher=[[Elsevier]] |work=Scopus preview |accessdate=2019-01-24}}</ref>\nAccording to the ''[[Journal Citation Reports]]'', the journal has a 2017 [[impact factor]] of 2.968.<ref name=WoS>{{cite book |year=2018 |chapter=Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology |title=2017 Journal Citation Reports |publisher=[[Clarivate Analytics]] |edition=Science OR Social Sciences |series=[[Web of Science]] |title-link=Journal Citation Reports}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.beilstein-journals.org/bjnano}}\n\n[[Category:Nanotechnology journals]]\n[[Category:Continuous journals]]\n[[Category:English-language journals]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 2010]]\n", "name_user": "46.5.11.87", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beilstein_Journal_of_Nanotechnology"}
{"title_page": "Universiti Utara Malaysia", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox University\n| name            = Northern University of Malaysia\n| native_name     = {{nobold|{{native name|ms|Universiti Utara Malaysia}}<!--end nobold:-->}}\n| image_name      = Universiti Utara Malaysia logo.jpg\n| image_size      = 220px\n| motto           = Ilmu, Budi, Bakti<ref>{{cite web|title=Falsafah|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/ms/visitor/the-university/philosophy|publisher=UUM|accessdate=11 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812202215/http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/ms/visitor/the-university/philosophy|archive-date=12 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| mottoeng        = Scholarship, Virtue, Service<ref>{{cite web|title=Philosophy|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/philosophy|publisher=UUM|accessdate=11 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913134519/http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/philosophy|archive-date=13 September 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| established     = 1984\n| type            = [[Public university|Public]]\n| chancellor      = HRH [[Sallehuddin of Kedah|Sultan Sallehuddin]]\n| vice_chancellor = [[Professor]] Dr Safieee The Cutiee <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/board-of-directors|title=Board of Directors|website=Universiti Utara Malaysia|accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n| students        = 30,670\n| undergrad       = 22,932<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.web.malaysia-students.com/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum|title=UUM|accessdate=23 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122215101/http://web.malaysia-students.com/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum|archive-date=22 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n| postgrad        = 4,597\n| doctoral        = \n| other           = 3,141\n| city            = [[Sintok]], [[Kedah]]\n| country         = [[Malaysia]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|6|27|28|N|100|30|20|E|region:MY_type:edu_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=inline,title}}\n| campus          = [[Sintok]] (main campus) and [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n| affiliations    = [[Association of Southeast Asian Institutions of Higher Learning|ASAIHL]], [[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]],<ref>http://www.acu.ac.uk/institutions/search?code=MY</ref> [[Federation of the Universities of the Islamic World|FUIW]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuiw.org/universities.php?l%3D1%26p%3D1%26cc%3Dmy |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050126075634/http://www.fuiw.org/universities.php?l=1&p=1&cc=my |archivedate=26 January 2005 }}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|uum.edu.my}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Universiti Utara Malaysia''' ('''UUM'''; [[English language|English]]: ''Northern University of Malaysia'') was established on 16 February 1984 under the Universiti Utara Malaysia 1984 Order. The university was corporatised on 23 April 1998.\n\nIt is in [[Sintok]], [[Kedah]]. It is known as a management university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.studymalaysia.com/where/profile.php?code=UUM|title=Institution Profile UUM| publisher=Study Malaysia|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> UUM was ranked in the bracket of 591\u2014600 in the [[QS World University Rankings]] 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum#wur|title=Universiti Utara Malaysia| publisher=Quacquarelli Symonds|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe construction planning began in August 1983 when the [[Ministry of Education (Malaysia)|Ministry of Education]] began to plan the university. On 19 October 1983, the Cabinet gave its approval for this project in Kedah. At that time, the project was called \"The Sixth University Project\". Several months later, the temporary office of the Sixth University, officially named Universiti Utara Malaysia (UUM), was officially opened on 15 February 1984 in Jitra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.studymalaysia.com/where/profile.php?code=UUM|title=Institution Profile UUM| publisher=Study Malaysia|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> \n\nFour months after its official opening, the UUM office was relocated to the provisional Darul Aman Campus in [[Jitra]], in June 1984, when the first phase of the project had been completed. The first academic year began in June 1984. The Darul Aman Campus was on a 62-acre tract of land in [[Bandar Darulaman]]. It was 18&nbsp;km north of Alor Setar and 4.8&nbsp;km from Jitra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/about-uum|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913134458/http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/about-uum|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2013|title=About UUM|publisher=UUM|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the planning of a permanent campus had begun. It was to be built on an area of 1,061 hectares in Sintok (in the district of Kubang Pasu), 48 km north of Alor Setar and 10 km east of [[Changlun]], a small town along the North-South Highway, near the Malaysia-Thai border.\n\nThe permanent UUM campus, referred to as the Sintok Campus, began operations on 15 September 1990. In a former tin mining area, it is in a valley of lush tropical forests, embraced by blue hills, and watered by two rivers that flow along the middle of the campus. The rivers are Sungai Sintok and Sungai Badak.\n\nThe MYR580 million Sintok Campus was opened on 17 February 2004 by the Royal Chancellor, His Royal Highness [[Abdul Halim of Kedah|Sultan Abdul Halim Mu\u2019adzam Shah]]. The main buildings are the Sultanah Bahiyah Library, the Chancellery, the Sultan Badlishah Mosque, the Mu\u2019adzam Shah Hall, the Tan Sri Othman Hall, the Sports Complex, the Varsity Mall, the Budi Siswa building, the Convention Complex, and the buildings that house the departments of the academic colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/about-uum|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913134458/http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/about-uum|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2013|title=About UUM|publisher=UUM|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, a restructuring of the university academic system was undertaken. Thirteen faculties were merged and streamed into three main academic colleges: UUM COB (UUM College of Business), UUM CAS (UUM College of Arts and Sciences), and UUM COLGIS (UUM College of Law, Government and International Studies).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum/undergrad|title=Universiti Utara Malaysia|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:Northern University of Malaysia.JPG|thumb|Sintok Campus of UUM]]\n===Sintok Campus===\nThe main campus is on a 1,061 hectare site in Sintok, Kedah. The campus is 48 km north of Alor Setar and 10 km south of the Bukit Kayu Hitam and are near the [[Malaysia-Thailand border]]. Other towns near UUM are [[Jitra]] and [[Changlun]].\n\nDue to its vast land area, the university has used 107 hectares of forest to develop facilities open for use by outsiders. Thus the campus has evolved into an open campus where outsiders and tourists visit. Among the facilities are a picnic area, a nine-hole golf course, a go-kart circuit, a shooting and archery range, and an equestrian site.\n\nThe training base and facilities for the [[Malaysian National Service]] Programme (PLKN) was on the campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staging.ispkn.my/plkn-info/en/camp/camp-list/kedah/kem-plkn-sintok-uum-sintok/|title=PLKN Sintok Camp|accessdate=24 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201173711/http://staging.ispkn.my/plkn-info/en/camp/camp-list/kedah/kem-plkn-sintok-uum-sintok/|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Kuala Lumpur Campus===\nUUMKL Campus is the first UUM fully owned study centre outside Sintok and operated directly by UUM. It is a non-residential campus which occupies a nine storey building in the city center along Jalan Raja Muda Abdul Aziz in the Kampung Baru area and adjacent to Chow Kit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uumkl.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/tutorials|title=About Us|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> \n\n==Academics==\n\n===College Of Business===\nInitially, the business and management courses were delivered under a faculty system. In 2008, the faculties were merged to form the College of Business. The curriculum includes business administration, accountancy, finance, economics, banking, marketing, human resource management, insurance and risk management, Islamic banking and finance, muamalat, operations management, and technology management.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cob.uum.edu.my/index.php/about-us/introduction|title=Introduction to UUMCOB|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Faculties====\n* Graduate School: Othman Yeop Abdullah Graduate School of Business (OYAGSB)<ref>http://oyagsb.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n  Note: OYAGSB became an independent school in 2013  \n* School of Business Management<ref>http://sbm.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Islamic Business<ref>http://www.ibs.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Accountancy<ref>http://www.soa.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Economics, Finance & Banking<ref>http://www.sefb.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Technology & Logistics Management<ref>http://www.stmlportal.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n\n===College of Arts and Sciences===\nThe College of Arts and Sciences (UUM CAS) was formed on 1 January 2008. UUM CAS consists of five academic divisions \u2013 Applied Sciences, Educational Studies, Humanities, Physical Sciences, and Social Sciences \u2013 and each is headed by a chairperson.\n\nUnder the umbrella of UUM CAS, the Applied Sciences division caters for the cross-disciplinary programmes of IT, Computer Science, Multimedia and Decision Science programmes. Research interests include algorithms, web and mobile, software engineering, computer networking, intelligent and information systems, knowledge management, and decision analysis. \n\nPhysical Sciences focuses on statistics and mathematics with research interests spanning across the field of statistics and mathematics.\n\nThe Humanities and Social Sciences division explores the human condition to better understand our roots, our belief and the best way to express ourselves. The discipline includes history, nationhood, religion, language, communication and media technology.\n\nThe Education division produces future educators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cas.uum.edu.my/index.php/about-us|title=About UUM CAS|publisher=UUM CAS|accessdate=23 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202093404/http://cas.uum.edu.my/index.php/about-us|archive-date=2 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Faculties====\n* Graduate School: Awang Had Salleh Graduate School of Arts and Sciences<ref>http://www.ahsgs.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Computing<ref>http://www.soc.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Education and Modern Language\n* School of Multimedia Technology & Communication<ref>http://www.smmtc.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Quantitative Sciences<ref>http://www.sqs.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Social Development<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ssd.uum.edu.my/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201224015/http://www.ssd.uum.edu.my/ |archive-date=1 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===College of Law, Government and International Studies===\nThe Faculty of Public Management and Law (FPAU) was established on 16 November 2003 consisting of three departments: Public Management; Development Management; and Law. Since its inception, FPAU has offered three academic programs at the undergraduate level with honours and six programs at the postgraduate level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colgis.uum.edu.my/index.php/about-us/history-of-colgis|title=History of Colgis|publisher=UUM Colgis|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> In 2008, the faculties was restructured and grouped under the College of Law, Government and International Studies (COLGIS).\n\n====Faculties====\n* Graduate School: Ghazali Shafie Graduate School of Government<ref>http://gsgsg.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Government<ref>http://sog.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Law<ref>http://sol.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of International Studies<ref>http://soisuum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Tourism, Hospitality & Environmental Management<ref>http://www.sthem.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=8% | Year\n! width=8% | Rank\n! width=25% | Valuer\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2012||align=\"center\"|251\u2014300||align=\"center\"| [[QS Asian University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2013||align=\"center\"|201\u2014250||align=\"center\"| [[QS Asian University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2014||align=\"center\"|201\u2014250||align=\"center\"| [[QS Asian University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2015||align=\"center\"|191\u2014200||align=\"center\"| [[QS Asian University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2015||align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\" |701+<ref name=\"QS\" /> ||align=\"center\" rowspan=\"6\" | [[QS World University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2016\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2017\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2018||align=\"center\"|701\u2014750<ref name=\"QS\" />\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2019||align=\"center\"|601\u2014650<ref name=\"QS\" />\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2020||align=\"center\"|591\u2014600<ref name=\"QS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum#wurs|title=Universiti Utara Malaysia| publisher=Quacquarelli Symonds|accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Malaysia]]\n* [[Education in Malaysia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Northern University of Malaysia}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.uum.edu.my/}}\n\n{{Universities in Malaysia}}\n{{ASEAN University Network |state=collapsed}}\n{{Northern Corridor Economic Region}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Utara Malaysia}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kedah]]\n[[Category:Public universities in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Northern Corridor Economic Region]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Malaysia]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox University\n| name            = Northern University of Malaysia\n| native_name     = {{nobold|{{native name|ms|Universiti Utara Malaysia}}<!--end nobold:-->}}\n| image_name      = Universiti Utara Malaysia logo.jpg\n| image_size      = 220px\n| motto           = Ilmu, Budi, Bakti<ref>{{cite web|title=Falsafah|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/ms/visitor/the-university/philosophy|publisher=UUM|accessdate=11 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812202215/http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/ms/visitor/the-university/philosophy|archive-date=12 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| mottoeng        = Scholarship, Virtue, Service<ref>{{cite web|title=Philosophy|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/philosophy|publisher=UUM|accessdate=11 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913134519/http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/philosophy|archive-date=13 September 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| established     = 1984\n| type            = [[Public university|Public]]\n| chancellor      = HRH [[Sallehuddin of Kedah|Sultan Sallehuddin]]\n| vice_chancellor = [[Professor]] Dr Ahmad Bashawir bin Abdul Ghani<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/board-of-directors|title=Board of Directors|website=Universiti Utara Malaysia|accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n| students        = 30,670\n| undergrad       = 22,932<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.web.malaysia-students.com/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum|title=UUM|accessdate=23 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122215101/http://web.malaysia-students.com/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum|archive-date=22 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n| postgrad        = 4,597\n| doctoral        = \n| other           = 3,141\n| city            = [[Sintok]], [[Kedah]]\n| country         = [[Malaysia]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|6|27|28|N|100|30|20|E|region:MY_type:edu_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=inline,title}}\n| campus          = [[Sintok]] (main campus) and [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n| affiliations    = [[Association of Southeast Asian Institutions of Higher Learning|ASAIHL]], [[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]],<ref>http://www.acu.ac.uk/institutions/search?code=MY</ref> [[Federation of the Universities of the Islamic World|FUIW]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuiw.org/universities.php?l%3D1%26p%3D1%26cc%3Dmy |title=Archived copy |accessdate=16 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050126075634/http://www.fuiw.org/universities.php?l=1&p=1&cc=my |archivedate=26 January 2005 }}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|uum.edu.my}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Universiti Utara Malaysia''' ('''UUM'''; [[English language|English]]: ''Northern University of Malaysia'') was established on 16 February 1984 under the Universiti Utara Malaysia 1984 Order. The university was corporatised on 23 April 1998.\n\nIt is in [[Sintok]], [[Kedah]]. It is known as a management university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.studymalaysia.com/where/profile.php?code=UUM|title=Institution Profile UUM| publisher=Study Malaysia|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> UUM was ranked in the bracket of 591\u2014600 in the [[QS World University Rankings]] 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum#wur|title=Universiti Utara Malaysia| publisher=Quacquarelli Symonds|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> \n\n==History==\nThe construction planning began in August 1983 when the [[Ministry of Education (Malaysia)|Ministry of Education]] began to plan the university. On 19 October 1983, the Cabinet gave its approval for this project in Kedah. At that time, the project was called \"The Sixth University Project\". Several months later, the temporary office of the Sixth University, officially named Universiti Utara Malaysia (UUM), was officially opened on 15 February 1984 in Jitra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.studymalaysia.com/where/profile.php?code=UUM|title=Institution Profile UUM| publisher=Study Malaysia|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> \n\nFour months after its official opening, the UUM office was relocated to the provisional Darul Aman Campus in [[Jitra]], in June 1984, when the first phase of the project had been completed. The first academic year began in June 1984. The Darul Aman Campus was on a 62-acre tract of land in [[Bandar Darulaman]]. It was 18&nbsp;km north of Alor Setar and 4.8&nbsp;km from Jitra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/about-uum|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913134458/http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/about-uum|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2013|title=About UUM|publisher=UUM|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the planning of a permanent campus had begun. It was to be built on an area of 1,061 hectares in Sintok (in the district of Kubang Pasu), 48 km north of Alor Setar and 10 km east of [[Changlun]], a small town along the North-South Highway, near the Malaysia-Thai border.\n\nThe permanent UUM campus, referred to as the Sintok Campus, began operations on 15 September 1990. In a former tin mining area, it is in a valley of lush tropical forests, embraced by blue hills, and watered by two rivers that flow along the middle of the campus. The rivers are Sungai Sintok and Sungai Badak.\n\nThe MYR580 million Sintok Campus was opened on 17 February 2004 by the Royal Chancellor, His Royal Highness [[Abdul Halim of Kedah|Sultan Abdul Halim Mu\u2019adzam Shah]]. The main buildings are the Sultanah Bahiyah Library, the Chancellery, the Sultan Badlishah Mosque, the Mu\u2019adzam Shah Hall, the Tan Sri Othman Hall, the Sports Complex, the Varsity Mall, the Budi Siswa building, the Convention Complex, and the buildings that house the departments of the academic colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/about-uum|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913134458/http://www.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/visitor/the-university/about-uum|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2013|title=About UUM|publisher=UUM|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, a restructuring of the university academic system was undertaken. Thirteen faculties were merged and streamed into three main academic colleges: UUM COB (UUM College of Business), UUM CAS (UUM College of Arts and Sciences), and UUM COLGIS (UUM College of Law, Government and International Studies).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum/undergrad|title=Universiti Utara Malaysia|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:Northern University of Malaysia.JPG|thumb|Sintok Campus of UUM]]\n===Sintok Campus===\nThe main campus is on a 1,061 hectare site in Sintok, Kedah. The campus is 48 km north of Alor Setar and 10 km south of the Bukit Kayu Hitam and are near the [[Malaysia-Thailand border]]. Other towns near UUM are [[Jitra]] and [[Changlun]].\n\nDue to its vast land area, the university has used 107 hectares of forest to develop facilities open for use by outsiders. Thus the campus has evolved into an open campus where outsiders and tourists visit. Among the facilities are a picnic area, a nine-hole golf course, a go-kart circuit, a shooting and archery range, and an equestrian site.\n\nThe training base and facilities for the [[Malaysian National Service]] Programme (PLKN) was on the campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staging.ispkn.my/plkn-info/en/camp/camp-list/kedah/kem-plkn-sintok-uum-sintok/|title=PLKN Sintok Camp|accessdate=24 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201173711/http://staging.ispkn.my/plkn-info/en/camp/camp-list/kedah/kem-plkn-sintok-uum-sintok/|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Kuala Lumpur Campus===\nUUMKL Campus is the first UUM fully owned study centre outside Sintok and operated directly by UUM. It is a non-residential campus which occupies a nine storey building in the city center along Jalan Raja Muda Abdul Aziz in the Kampung Baru area and adjacent to Chow Kit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uumkl.uum.edu.my/index.php/en/tutorials|title=About Us|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> \n\n==Academics==\n\n===College Of Business===\nInitially, the business and management courses were delivered under a faculty system. In 2008, the faculties were merged to form the College of Business. The curriculum includes business administration, accountancy, finance, economics, banking, marketing, human resource management, insurance and risk management, Islamic banking and finance, muamalat, operations management, and technology management.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cob.uum.edu.my/index.php/about-us/introduction|title=Introduction to UUMCOB|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Faculties====\n* Graduate School: Othman Yeop Abdullah Graduate School of Business (OYAGSB)<ref>http://oyagsb.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n  Note: OYAGSB became an independent school in 2013  \n* School of Business Management<ref>http://sbm.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Islamic Business<ref>http://www.ibs.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Accountancy<ref>http://www.soa.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Economics, Finance & Banking<ref>http://www.sefb.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Technology & Logistics Management<ref>http://www.stmlportal.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n\n===College of Arts and Sciences===\nThe College of Arts and Sciences (UUM CAS) was formed on 1 January 2008. UUM CAS consists of five academic divisions \u2013 Applied Sciences, Educational Studies, Humanities, Physical Sciences, and Social Sciences \u2013 and each is headed by a chairperson.\n\nUnder the umbrella of UUM CAS, the Applied Sciences division caters for the cross-disciplinary programmes of IT, Computer Science, Multimedia and Decision Science programmes. Research interests include algorithms, web and mobile, software engineering, computer networking, intelligent and information systems, knowledge management, and decision analysis. \n\nPhysical Sciences focuses on statistics and mathematics with research interests spanning across the field of statistics and mathematics.\n\nThe Humanities and Social Sciences division explores the human condition to better understand our roots, our belief and the best way to express ourselves. The discipline includes history, nationhood, religion, language, communication and media technology.\n\nThe Education division produces future educators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cas.uum.edu.my/index.php/about-us|title=About UUM CAS|publisher=UUM CAS|accessdate=23 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202093404/http://cas.uum.edu.my/index.php/about-us|archive-date=2 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Faculties====\n* Graduate School: Awang Had Salleh Graduate School of Arts and Sciences<ref>http://www.ahsgs.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Computing<ref>http://www.soc.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Education and Modern Language\n* School of Multimedia Technology & Communication<ref>http://www.smmtc.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Quantitative Sciences<ref>http://www.sqs.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Social Development<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ssd.uum.edu.my/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201224015/http://www.ssd.uum.edu.my/ |archive-date=1 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===College of Law, Government and International Studies===\nThe Faculty of Public Management and Law (FPAU) was established on 16 November 2003 consisting of three departments: Public Management; Development Management; and Law. Since its inception, FPAU has offered three academic programs at the undergraduate level with honours and six programs at the postgraduate level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colgis.uum.edu.my/index.php/about-us/history-of-colgis|title=History of Colgis|publisher=UUM Colgis|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> In 2008, the faculties was restructured and grouped under the College of Law, Government and International Studies (COLGIS).\n\n====Faculties====\n* Graduate School: Ghazali Shafie Graduate School of Government<ref>http://gsgsg.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Government<ref>http://sog.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Law<ref>http://sol.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of International Studies<ref>http://soisuum.edu.my/</ref>\n* School of Tourism, Hospitality & Environmental Management<ref>http://www.sthem.uum.edu.my/</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=8% | Year\n! width=8% | Rank\n! width=25% | Valuer\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2012||align=\"center\"|251\u2014300||align=\"center\"| [[QS Asian University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2013||align=\"center\"|201\u2014250||align=\"center\"| [[QS Asian University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2014||align=\"center\"|201\u2014250||align=\"center\"| [[QS Asian University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2015||align=\"center\"|191\u2014200||align=\"center\"| [[QS Asian University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2015||align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\" |701+<ref name=\"QS\" /> ||align=\"center\" rowspan=\"6\" | [[QS World University Rankings]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2016\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2017\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2018||align=\"center\"|701\u2014750<ref name=\"QS\" />\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2019||align=\"center\"|601\u2014650<ref name=\"QS\" />\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2020||align=\"center\"|591\u2014600<ref name=\"QS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/universiti-utara-malaysia-uum#wurs|title=Universiti Utara Malaysia| publisher=Quacquarelli Symonds|accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Malaysia]]\n* [[Education in Malaysia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Northern University of Malaysia}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.uum.edu.my/}}\n\n{{Universities in Malaysia}}\n{{ASEAN University Network |state=collapsed}}\n{{Northern Corridor Economic Region}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Utara Malaysia}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kedah]]\n[[Category:Public universities in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Northern Corridor Economic Region]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Malaysia]]\n", "name_user": "115.132.161.34", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universiti_Utara_Malaysia"}
